\layout Section

Quantization of harmonic oscillator
\layout Standard

This section serves as a very quick reminder of quantum mechanics of harmonic
 oscillators.
 It is assumed that the reader is already familiar with such notions as
 Schrödinger equation and Heisenberg picture.
\layout Subsection

Canonical quantization
\layout Standard

A classical harmonic oscillator is described by a coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $q(t)$
\end_inset 

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ddot{q}+\omega^{2}q=0,\label{eq:oscillator}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset 

 is a real constant.
 The general solution of this equation can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
q(t)=ae^{i\omega t}+a^{*}e^{-i\omega t},\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

 is a (complex-valued) constant.
 We may identify the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

ground state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 of the oscillator as the state without motion, i.e.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $q(t)\equiv0$
\end_inset 

.
 This is obviously the lowest-energy state of the oscillator.
\layout Standard

The quantum theory of the oscillator is obtained by the standard procedure
 known as 
\series bold 
canonical quantization
\series default 
.
 Canonical quantization does not apply directly to an equation of motion.
 Rather, we first need to describe the system using the Hamiltonian formalism,
 which means that we must start with the Lagrangian action principle.
 The classical equation of motion\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:oscillator}

\end_inset 

) is reformulated as a condition to extremize the action,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int L(q,\dot{q})dt=\int\left[\frac{1}{2}\dot{q}^{2}-\frac{1}{2}\omega^{2}q^{2}\right]dt,\]

\end_inset 

where the function 
\begin_inset Formula $L(q,\dot{q})$
\end_inset 

 is the 
\series bold 
Lagrangian
\series default 
.
 (For simplicity, we assumed a unit mass of the oscillator.) Then we define
 the 
\series bold 
canonical momentum
\series default 

\begin_inset Formula \[
p\equiv\frac{\partial L(q,\dot{q})}{\partial\dot{q}}=\dot{q},\]

\end_inset 

and perform a Legendre transformation to find the 
\series bold 
Hamiltonian
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
H(p,q)\equiv\left[p\dot{q}-L\right]_{\dot{q}\rightarrow p}=\frac{1}{2}p^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\omega^{2}q^{2}.\]

\end_inset 

The Hamiltonian equations of motion are
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{q}=p,\quad\dot{p}=-\omega^{2}q.\]

\end_inset 

Finally, we replace the classical coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $q(t)$
\end_inset 

 and the momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)$
\end_inset 

 by Hermitian operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}(t)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}(t)$
\end_inset 

 satisfying the same equations of motion,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{\hat{q}}=\hat{p},\quad\dot{\hat{p}}=-\omega^{2}\hat{q},\]

\end_inset 

and additionally postulate the Heisenberg commutation relation 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\hat{q}(t),\hat{p}(t)\right]=i\hbar.\label{eq:Heisenberg pq}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H(p,q)$
\end_inset 

 is also promoted to an operator,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{H}\equiv H(\hat{p},\hat{q})=\frac{1}{2}\hat{p}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\omega^{2}\hat{q}^{2}.\]

\end_inset 

All the quantum operators pertaining to the oscillator act in a certain
 vector space of 
\series bold 
quantum states 
\series default 
or
\series bold 
 wavefunctions
\series default 
.
 (This space must be a Hilbert space; see Appendix\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Hilbert-spaces-and}

\end_inset 

 for details.) Vectors from this space are usually denoted using Dirac's
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

bra-ket
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 symbols: vectors are denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|b\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, and the corresponding covectors by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a\right|$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle b\right|$
\end_inset 

, etc.
 Presently, we use the
\series bold 
 Heisenberg picture
\series default 
, in which the operators depend on time but the quantum states are time-independ
ent.
 This picture is more convenient for developing quantum field theory than
 the 
\series bold 
Schrödinger picture
\series default 
 where operators are time-independent but wavefunctions change with time.
 Therefore, we shall continue to treat the harmonic oscillator in the Heisenberg
 picture.
 We shall not need to use the coordinate or momentum representation of wavefunct
ions.
\layout Subsection

Creation and annihilation operators
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Creation-and-annihilation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

classical ground state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}(t)\equiv0$
\end_inset 

 is impossible in quantum theory because in that case the commutation relation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Heisenberg pq}

\end_inset 

) could not be satisfied by any 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}(t)$
\end_inset 

.
 Hence, a quantum oscillator cannot be completely at rest, and its lowest-energy
 state (called the 
\series bold 
ground state
\series default 
 or the 
\series bold 
vacuum state
\series default 
) has a more complicated structure.
 The standard way of describing quantum oscillators is through the introduction
 of the creation and annihilation operators.
\layout Standard

From now on, we use the units where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar=1$
\end_inset 

.
 The Heisenberg commutation relation becomes
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\hat{q}(t),\hat{p}(t)\right]=i.\label{eq:Heisenberg h1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 We now define the 
\series bold 
annihilation operator
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{-}(t)$
\end_inset 

 and its Hermitian conjugate, 
\series bold 
creation operator
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{+}(t)$
\end_inset 

, by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{a}^{\pm}(t)=\sqrt{\frac{\omega}{2}}\left[\hat{q}(t)\mp\frac{i}{\omega}\hat{p}(t)\right].\]

\end_inset 

 These operators are not Hermitian since 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{a}^{-})^{\dagger}=\hat{a}^{+}$
\end_inset 

.
 The equation of motion for the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{-}(t)$
\end_inset 

 is straightforward to derive,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\hat{a}^{-}(t)=-i\omega\hat{a}^{-}(t).\label{eq:aminus equ 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

(The Hermitian conjugate operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{+}(t)$
\end_inset 

 satisfies the complex conjugate equation.) The solution of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:aminus equ 1}

\end_inset 

) with the initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\hat{a}^{-}(t)\right|_{t=0}=\hat{a}_{0}^{-}$
\end_inset 

 can be readily found,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{a}^{-}(t)=\hat{a}_{0}^{-}e^{-i\omega t}.\label{eq:time dep a}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

It is helpful to introduce time-independent operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{0}^{\pm}\equiv\hat{a}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 and to write the time-dependent phase factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\omega t}$
\end_inset 

 explicitly.
 For instance, we find that the canonical variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}(t)$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}(t)$
\end_inset 

 are related to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{p}(t)=\sqrt{\omega}\frac{\hat{a}^{-}e^{-i\omega t}-\hat{a}^{+}e^{i\omega t}}{i\sqrt{2}},\quad\hat{q}(t)=\frac{\hat{a}^{-}e^{-i\omega t}+\hat{a}^{+}e^{i\omega t}}{\sqrt{2\omega}}.\label{eq:p q through am ap}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

From now on, we shall only use the 
\emph on 
time-independent
\emph default 
 operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

.
 Using Eqs.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Heisenberg h1}

\end_inset 

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:p q through am ap}

\end_inset 

), it is easy to show that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
[\hat{a}^{-},\hat{a}^{+}]=1.\]

\end_inset 

 Using the relations\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:p q through am ap}

\end_inset 

), the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}$
\end_inset 

 can be expressed through the creation and annihilation operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{H}=\left(\hat{a}^{+}\hat{a}^{-}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\omega.\label{eq:Ham thru aa}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Subsection

Particle number eigenstates
\layout Standard

Quantum states of the oscillator are described by vectors in an appropriate
 (infinite-dimensional) Hilbert space.
 A complete basis in this space is made of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, ..., which are called the occupation number states or particle number states.
 The construction of these states is well known, and we briefly review it
 here for completeness.
 
\layout Standard

It is seen from Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Ham thru aa}

\end_inset 

) that the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}$
\end_inset 

 are bounded from below by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\omega$
\end_inset 

.
 It is then 
\emph on 
assumed
\emph default 
 that the ground state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 exists and is unique.
 Using this assumption and the commutation relations, one can show that
 the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{a}^{-}\left|0\right\rangle =0.\]

\end_inset 

 (This derivation is standard and we omit it here.) Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}\left|0\right\rangle =\frac{1}{2}\omega\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, which means that the ground state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 indeed has the lowest possible energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\omega$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The 
\series bold 
excited states
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,...$
\end_inset 

, are defined by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|n\right\rangle =\frac{1}{\sqrt{n!}}(\hat{a}^{+})^{n}\left|0\right\rangle .\label{eq:excited state def}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The factors 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n!}$
\end_inset 

 are needed for normalization, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle m|n\right\rangle =\delta_{mn}$
\end_inset 

.
 It is easy to see that every state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is an eigenstate of the Hamiltonian,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{H}\left|n\right\rangle =\left(n+\frac{1}{2}\right)\omega\left|n\right\rangle .\]

\end_inset 

In other words, the energy of the oscillator is 
\emph on 
quantized
\emph default 
 (not continuous) and is measured in discrete 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

quanta
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, we might interpret the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 as describing the presence of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

quanta
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 of energy or 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

particles,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 each 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

particle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 having the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset 

.
 (In normal units, the energy of each quantum is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega$
\end_inset 

, which is the famous Planck formula for the energy quantum.) The operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}\equiv\hat{a}^{+}\hat{a}^{-}$
\end_inset 

 is called the 
\series bold 
particle number
\series default 
 operator.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}\left|n\right\rangle =n\left|n\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, the states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 are also called 
\series bold 
particle number
\series default 
 eigenstates.
 This terminology is motivated by the applications in quantum field theory
 (as we shall see below).
\layout Standard

To get a feeling of what the ground state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 looks like, one can compute the expectation values of the coordinate and
 the momentum in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 For instance, using Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:p q through am ap}

\end_inset 

) we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\left\langle 0\right|\hat{q}(t)\left|0\right\rangle  & =0,\quad\left\langle 0\right|\hat{p}(t)\left|0\right\rangle =0,\\
\left\langle 0\right|\hat{q}^{2}(t)\left|0\right\rangle  & =\frac{1}{2\omega},\quad\left\langle 0\right|\hat{p}^{2}(t)\left|0\right\rangle =\frac{\omega}{2}.\end{align*}

\end_inset 

It follows that the ground state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 of the oscillator exhibits fluctuations of both the coordinate and the
 momentum around a zero mean value.
 The typical value of the fluctuation in the coordinate is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q\sim\left(2\omega\right)^{-1/2}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Section

Quantization of scalar field
\layout Standard

The quantum theory of fields is built on two essential foundations: the
 classical theory of fields and the quantum mechanics of harmonic oscillators.
\layout Subsection

Classical field
\layout Standard

A 
\series bold 
classical field
\series default 
 is described by a function of spacetime, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset 

, characterizing the local strength or intensity of the field.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset 

 is a three-dimensional coordinate in space and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 is the time (in some reference frame).
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset 

 may have real values, complex values, or values in some finite-dimensional
 vector space.
 For example, the electromagnetic field is described by the 4-potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}(\mathbf{x},t)$
\end_inset 

, which is a function whose values are 4-vectors.
 
\layout Standard

The simplest example of a field is a 
\series bold 
real scalar
\series default 
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset 

; its values are real numbers.
 A 
\series bold 
free, massive
\series default 
 scalar field satisfies the Klein-Gordon equation
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed false

\layout Standard

To simplify the formulas, we shall (almost always) use the units in which
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar=c=1$
\end_inset 

.
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\partial^{2}\phi}{\partial t^{2}}-\sum_{j=1}^{3}\frac{\partial^{2}\phi}{\partial x_{j}^{2}}+m^{2}\phi\equiv\ddot{\phi}-\Delta\phi+m^{2}\phi\equiv\partial_{\mu}\partial^{\mu}\phi+m^{2}\phi=0.\label{eq:KGequ}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset 

 is the 
\series bold 
mass
\series default 
 of the field.
 The solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)\equiv0$
\end_inset 

 is the classical vacuum state (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

no field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

To simplify the equations of motion, it is convenient to use the spatial
 Fourier decomposition,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)=\int\frac{d^{3}\mathbf{k}}{(2\pi)^{3/2}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{x}}\phi_{\mathbf{k}}(t),\label{eq:phi dec}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where we integrate over all three-dimensional vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

.
 After the Fourier decomposition, the partial differential equation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:KGequ}

\end_inset 

) is replaced by infinitely many ordinary differential equations, with one
 equation for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ddot{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}+\left(k^{2}+m^{2}\right)\phi_{\mathbf{k}}=\ddot{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}+\omega_{k}^{2}\phi_{\mathbf{k}}=0,\quad\omega_{k}\equiv\sqrt{\left|\mathbf{k}\right|^{2}+m^{2}}.\]

\end_inset 

In other words, each function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\mathbf{k}}(t)$
\end_inset 

 satisfies the harmonic oscillator equation with the frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}$
\end_inset 

.
 The complex-valued functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\mathbf{k}}(t)$
\end_inset 

 are called the 
\series bold 
modes
\series default 
 of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

 (abbreviated from 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

Fourier modes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

).
 Note that the modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\mathbf{k}}(t)$
\end_inset 

 of a real field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{x},t)$
\end_inset 

 satisfy the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{\mathbf{k}})^{*}=\phi_{-\mathbf{k}}.$
\end_inset 

 
\layout Standard

The equation of motion\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:KGequ}

\end_inset 

