\layout Subsection

Quantization of scalar field
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Quantization-of-scalar}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The action\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:S phik1}

\end_inset 

) is analogous to that of a collection of infinitely many harmonic oscillators.
 Therefore, we may quantize each mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\mathbf{k}}(t)$
\end_inset 

 as a separate (complex-valued) harmonic oscillator.
 
\layout Standard

Let us begin with the Hamiltonian description of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{x},t)$
\end_inset 

.
 The action\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:field rel action}

\end_inset 

) must be thought of as an integral of the Lagrangian over 
\emph on 
time
\emph default 
 (but not over space), 
\begin_inset Formula $S[\phi]=\int L[\phi]\, dt$
\end_inset 

, so the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi]$
\end_inset 

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
L[\phi]=\int{\cal L}d^{3}\mathbf{x};\quad{\cal L}\equiv\frac{1}{2}\eta^{\mu\nu}\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi\right)\left(\partial_{\nu}\phi\right)-\frac{1}{2}m^{2}\phi^{2},\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal L}$
\end_inset 

 is the 
\series bold 
Lagrangian
\series default 
 
\series bold 
density
\series default 
.
 To define the canonical momenta and the Hamiltonian, one must use the Lagrangia
n 
\begin_inset Formula $L[\phi]$
\end_inset 

 rather than the Lagrangian density 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal L}$
\end_inset 

.
 Hence, the momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset 

 are computed as the functional derivatives
\begin_inset Formula \[
\pi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)\equiv\frac{\delta L\left[\phi\right]}{\delta\dot{\phi}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)}=\dot{\phi}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right),\]

\end_inset 

 and then the classical Hamiltonian is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H=\int\pi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)\dot{\phi}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)d^{3}\mathbf{x}-L=\frac{1}{2}\int d^{3}\mathbf{x}\left[\pi^{2}+(\nabla\phi)^{2}+m^{2}\phi^{2}\right].\label{eq:field Ham}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

To quantize the field, we introduce the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset 

 with the standard commutation relations
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
[\hat{\phi}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right),\,\hat{\pi}\left(\mathbf{y},t\right)]=i\delta\left(\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{y}\right);\quad[\hat{\phi}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right),\,\hat{\phi}\left(\mathbf{y},t\right)]=[\hat{\pi}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right),\,\hat{\pi}\left(\mathbf{y},t\right)]=0.\label{eq:phi pi comm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\mathbf{k}}(t)$
\end_inset 

 also become operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}(t)$
\end_inset 

.
 The commutation relation for the modes can be derived from Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi pi comm}

\end_inset 

) by performing Fourier transforms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset 

.
 After some algebra, we find 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\hat{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}(t),\,\hat{\pi}_{\mathbf{k'}}(t)\right]=i\delta\left(\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{k}'\right).\label{eq:phi pi k comm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Note the 
\emph on 
plus
\emph default 
 sign in 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(\mathbf{k}_{1}+\mathbf{k}_{2})$
\end_inset 

: this is related to the fact that the variable which is conjugate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

 is not 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{-\mathbf{k}}=\hat{\pi}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset 

.
 
