\layout Standard

We now give a brief introduction to mode expansions, which offer a shorter
 and computationally convenient way to quantize fields.
 A more detailed treatment is given in Sec\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:chapter06}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The quantum mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}(t)$
\end_inset 

 can be expressed through the creation and annihilation operators, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}(t)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega_{k}}}\left(\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}e^{-i\omega_{k}t}+\hat{a}_{-\mathbf{k}}^{+}e^{i\omega_{k}t}\right).\]

\end_inset 

Substituting this into Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi dec}

\end_inset 

), we obtain the following expansion of the field operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\phi}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)=\int\frac{d^{3}\mathbf{k}}{(2\pi)^{3/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega_{k}}}\left[\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}e^{-i\omega_{k}t+i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{x}}+\hat{a}_{-\mathbf{k}}^{+}e^{i\omega_{k}t+i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{x}}\right],\]

\end_inset 

