\layout Section

Casimir effect
\layout Subsection

Zero-point energy
\layout Standard

The 
\series bold 
zero-point energy
\series default 
 is the energy of the vacuum state.
 We saw in Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Quantization-of-scalar}

\end_inset 

 that a quantum field is equivalent to a collection of infinitely many harmonic
 oscillators.
 If the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

 is in the vacuum state, each oscillator 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

 is in the ground state and has the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\omega_{k}$
\end_inset 

.
 Hence, the total zero-point energy of the field is the sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\omega_{k}$
\end_inset 

 over all wavenumbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

.
 This sum may be approximated by an integral in the following way: If one
 quantizes the field in a box of large but finite volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset 

, one will obtain the result that the zero-point energy 
\emph on 
density
\emph default 
 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{E_{0}}{V}=\int\frac{d^{3}\mathbf{k}}{\left(2\pi\right)^{3}}\frac{1}{2}\omega_{k}.\]

\end_inset 

 (A detailed computation can be found in the book [MW07].) Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}$
\end_inset 

 grows with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

, it is clear that the integral diverges.
 Taken at face value, this would indicate an infinite energy density of
 the vacuum state.
 Since any energy density leads to gravitational effects, the presence of
 a nonzero energy density in the vacuum state contradicts the experimental
 observation that empty space does not generate any gravitational force.
 The standard way to avoid this problem is to subtract this infinite quantity
 from the energy of the system (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

renormalization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 of zero-point energy).
 In other words, the ground state energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\omega_{k}$
\end_inset 

 is subtracted from the Hamiltonian of each oscillator 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

.
 A justification for this subtraction is that the ground state energy cannot
 be extracted from an oscillator, and that only the change in the oscillator's
 energy can be observed.
 
\layout Subsection

Casimir effect
\layout Standard

The Casimir effect is an experimentally verified prediction of quantum field
 theory.
 It is manifested by a force of attraction between two 
\emph on 
uncharged
\emph default 
 conducting plates in a vacuum.
 This force cannot be explained except by considering the zero-point energy
 of the quantized electromagnetic field.
 The presence of the conducting plates makes the electromagnetic field vanish
 on the surfaces of the plates.
 This boundary condition changes the structure of vacuum fluctuations of
 the field, which would normally be nonzero on the plates.
 This change causes a finite shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E$
\end_inset 

 of the zero-point energy, compared with the zero-point energy in empty
 space without the plates.
 The energy shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E=\Delta E(L)$
\end_inset 

 depends on the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

 between the plates, and it turns out that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E$
\end_inset 

 grows with 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

.
 As a result, it is energetically favorable for the plates to move closer
 together, which is manifested as the 
\series bold 
Casimir force 
\series default 
of attraction between the plates,
\begin_inset Formula \[
F(L)=-\frac{d}{dL}\left[\Delta E(L)\right].\]

\end_inset 

This theoretically predicted force has been confirmed by several experiments.
