\layout Subsection

Zero-point energy between plates
\layout Standard

A realistic description of the Casimir effect involves quantization of the
 electromagnetic field in the presence of conductors having certain dielectric
 properties; thermal fluctuations must also be taken into account.
 We shall drastically simplify the calculations by considering a 
\emph on 
massless scalar
\emph default 
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 in the flat 1+1-dimensional spacetime.
 To simulate the presence of the plates, we impose the following boundary
 conditions: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left.\phi(t,x)\right|_{x=0}=\left.\phi(t,x)\right|_{x=L}=0.\label{eq:Casimir cond}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The equation of motion for the classical field is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}^{2}\phi-\partial_{x}^{2}\phi=0$
\end_inset 

, and the general solution for the chosen boundary conditions is of the
 form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi(t,x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\left(A_{n}e^{-i\omega_{n}t}+B_{n}e^{i\omega_{n}t}\right)\sin\omega_{n}x,\quad\omega_{n}\equiv\frac{n\pi}{L}.\]

\end_inset 

 We shall now use this solution as a motivation for finding the appropriate
 mode expansion for the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

To quantize the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 in flat space, one would normally use the mode expansion
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\phi}(t,x)=\int\frac{dk}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega_{k}}}\left[\hat{a}_{k}^{-}e^{-i\omega_{k}t+ikx}+\hat{a}_{k}^{+}e^{i\omega_{k}t-ikx}\right].\]

\end_inset 

However, in the present case the only allowed modes are those satisfying
 Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Casimir cond}

\end_inset 

), so the above mode expansion cannot be used.
 To expand the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 into the allowed modes, we use the orthogonal system of functions
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{n}(x)=\sqrt{\frac{2}{L}}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{L}\]

\end_inset 

which vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=L$
\end_inset 

.
 These functions satisfy the orthogonality relation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{0}^{L}g_{m}(x)g_{n}(x)dx=\delta_{mn}.\]

\end_inset 

(The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2/L}$
\end_inset 

 is necessary for the correct normalization.) An arbitrary function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset 

 that vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=L$
\end_inset 

 can be expanded through the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}(x)$
\end_inset 

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
F(x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}F_{n}g_{n}(x),\]

\end_inset 

where the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are found as
\begin_inset Formula \[
F_{n}=\int_{0}^{L}F(x)g_{n}(x)dx.\]

\end_inset 

 Performing this decomposition for the field operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}(t,x)$
\end_inset 

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\phi}(t,x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\hat{\phi}_{n}(t)g_{n}(x),\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}_{n}(t)$
\end_inset 

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

-th mode of the field.
 The mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}_{n}(t)$
\end_inset 

 satisfies the oscillator equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ddot{\hat{\phi}}_{n}+\left(\frac{\pi n}{L}\right)^{2}\hat{\phi}_{n}\equiv\ddot{\hat{\phi}}_{n}+\omega_{n}^{2}\hat{\phi}_{n}=0,\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 whose general solution is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\phi}_{n}(t)=\hat{A}e^{-i\omega_{n}t}+\hat{B}e^{i\omega_{n}t},\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A},\hat{B}$
\end_inset 

 are operator-valued integration constants.
 After computing the correct normalization of these constants (see below),
 we obtain the the mode expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\phi}(t,x)=\sqrt{\frac{2}{L}}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{\sin\omega_{n}x}{\sqrt{2\omega_{n}}}\left[\hat{a}_{n}^{-}e^{-i\omega_{n}t}+\hat{a}_{n}^{+}e^{i\omega_{n}t}\right].\label{eq:Casimir norm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

We need to compute the energy of the field only between the plates, 
\begin_inset Formula $0<x<L$
\end_inset 

.
 After some calculations (see below), one can express the zero-point energy
 
\emph on 
per unit length
\emph default 
 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{0}\equiv\frac{1}{L}\left\langle 0\right|\hat{H}\left|0\right\rangle =\frac{1}{2L}\sum_{k}\omega_{k}=\frac{\pi}{2L^{2}}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}n.\label{eq:E0 div}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard
\noindent 

