\layout Subsection

Regularization and renormalization
\layout Standard

The zero-point energy density 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is divergent.
 However, in the presence of the plates the energy density diverges in a
 different way than in free space because 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}=\varepsilon_{0}(L)$
\end_inset 

 depends on the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

 between the plates.
 The zero-point energy density in free space can be thought of as the limit
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}(L)$
\end_inset 

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $L\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\varepsilon_{0}^{(\textrm{free})}=\lim_{L\rightarrow\infty}\varepsilon_{0}\left(L\right).\]

\end_inset 

When the zero-point energy is renormalized in free space, the infinite contribut
ion 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}^{(\textrm{free})}$
\end_inset 

 is subtracted.
 Thus we are motivated to subtract 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}^{(\textrm{free})}$
\end_inset 

 from the energy density 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}(L)$
\end_inset 

 and to expect to find a 
\emph on 
finite
\emph default 
 difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\varepsilon$
\end_inset 

 between these formally infinite quantities,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta\varepsilon\left(L\right)=\varepsilon_{0}\left(L\right)-\varepsilon_{0}^{(\textrm{free})}=\varepsilon_{0}\left(L\right)-\lim_{L\rightarrow\infty}\varepsilon_{0}\left(L\right).\label{eq:dE 0}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 In the remainder of the chapter we calculate this energy difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\varepsilon(L)$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Taken at face value, Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dE 0}

\end_inset 

) is meaningless because the difference between two infinite quantities
 is undefined.
 The standard way to deduce reasonable answers from infinities is a regularizati
on followed by a renormalization.
 A 
\series bold 
regularization
\series default 
 means introducing an extra parameter into the theory to make the divergent
 quantity finite unless that parameter is set to (say) zero.
 Such regularization parameters or 
\series bold 
cutoffs
\series default 
 can be chosen in many ways.
 After the regularization, one derives an asymptotic form of the divergent
 quantity at small values of the cutoff.
 This asymptotic may contain divergent powers and logarithms of the cutoff
 as well as finite terms.
 
\series bold 
Renormalization
\series default 
 means removing the divergent terms and leaving only the finite terms in
 the expression.
 (Of course, a suitable justification must be provided for subtracting the
 divergent terms.) After renormalization, the cutoff is set to zero and the
 remaining terms yield the final result.
 If the cutoff function is chosen incorrectly, the renormalization procedure
 will not succeed.
 It is usually possible to motivate the correct choice of the cutoff by
 physical considerations.
\layout Standard

We shall now apply this procedure to Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dE 0}

\end_inset 

).
 As a first step, a cutoff must be introduced into the divergent expression\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:E0 div}

\end_inset 

).
 One possibility is to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset 

 by the regularized quantity
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{0}\left(L;\alpha\right)=\frac{\pi}{2L^{2}}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}n\exp\left[-\frac{n\alpha}{L}\right],\label{eq:E0 reg}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 is the cutoff parameter.
 The regularized series converges for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset 

, while the original divergent expression is recovered in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\rightarrow0$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard
\noindent 

