\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Now we need to evaluate the regularized quantity\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:E0 reg}

\end_inset 

) and to analyze its asymptotic behavior at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\rightarrow0$
\end_inset 

.
 A straightforward computation gives
\begin_inset Formula \[
\varepsilon_{0}\left(L;\alpha\right)=-\frac{\pi}{2L}\frac{\partial}{\partial\alpha}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\exp\left[-\frac{n\alpha}{L}\right]=\frac{\pi}{2L^{2}}\frac{\exp\left(-\frac{\alpha}{L}\right)}{\left[1-\exp\left(-\frac{\alpha}{L}\right)\right]^{2}}.\]

\end_inset 

At 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\rightarrow0$
\end_inset 

 this expression can be expanded in a Laurent series,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{0}\left(L;\alpha\right)=\frac{\pi}{8L^{2}}\frac{1}{\sinh^{2}\frac{\alpha}{2L}}=\frac{\pi}{2\alpha^{2}}-\frac{\pi}{24L^{2}}+O\left(\alpha^{2}\right).\label{eq:E0 reg a}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The series\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:E0 reg a}

\end_inset 

) contains the singular term 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{2}\alpha^{-2}$
\end_inset 

, a finite term, and further terms that vanish as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\rightarrow0$
\end_inset 

.
 The crucial fact is that the singular term in Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:E0 reg a}

\end_inset 

) does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

.
 (This would not have happened if we chose the cutoff e.g.\SpecialChar ~
as 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-n\alpha}$
\end_inset 

.) The limit 
\begin_inset Formula $L\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset 

 in Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dE 0}

\end_inset 

) is taken 
\emph on 
before
\emph default 
 the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\rightarrow0$
\end_inset 

, so the divergent term 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{2}\alpha^{-2}$
\end_inset 

 cancels and the renormalized value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\varepsilon$
\end_inset 

 is finite,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta\varepsilon_{ren}(L)=\lim_{\alpha\rightarrow0}\left[\varepsilon_{0}\left(L;\alpha\right)-\lim_{L\rightarrow\infty}\varepsilon_{0}\left(L;\alpha\right)\right]=-\frac{\pi}{24L^{2}}.\label{eq:Cas ans}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The formula\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Cas ans}

\end_inset 

) is the main result of this chapter; the zero-point energy density is nonzero
 in the presence of plates at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=L$
\end_inset 

.
 The Casimir force between the plates is
\begin_inset Formula \[
F=-\frac{d}{dL}\Delta E=-\frac{d}{dL}\left(L\Delta\varepsilon_{ren}\right)=-\frac{\pi}{24L^{2}}.\]

\end_inset 

Since the force is negative, the plates are pulled toward each other.
