\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}(t)$
\end_inset 

.
 We shall examine this situation in detail in chapter\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:chapter06}

\end_inset 

.
 For now, let us consider a single harmonic oscillator with a time-dependent
 frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(t)$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Subsection

Quantization
\layout Standard

In the classical theory, the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $q(t)$
\end_inset 

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ddot{q}+\omega^{2}(t)q=0.\label{eq:osc var omega}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

An important example of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(t)$
\end_inset 

 is shown Fig.\SpecialChar ~

