The classical equation of motion\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:osc var omega}

\end_inset 

) can be derived from the Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula \[
L\left(t,q,\dot{q}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\dot{q}^{2}-\frac{1}{2}\omega(t)^{2}q^{2}.\]

\end_inset 

The corresponding canonical momentum is 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\dot{q}$
\end_inset 

, and the Hamiltonian is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H(p,q)=\frac{p^{2}}{2}+\omega^{2}(t)\frac{q^{2}}{2},\label{eq:classical H p q}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

which depends explicitly on the time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, we do not expect that energy is conserved in this system.
 (There is an external agent that drives 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(t)$
\end_inset 

 and may exchange energy with the oscillator.)
\layout Standard

A time-dependent oscillator can be quantized using the technique of creation
 and annihilation operators.
 By analogy with Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:p q through am ap}

\end_inset 

), we try the ansatz
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{q}(t)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(v(t)\hat{a}^{+}+v^{*}(t)\hat{a}^{-}\right),\quad\hat{p}(t)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\dot{v}(t)\hat{a}^{+}+\dot{v}^{*}(t)\hat{a}^{-}\right),\label{eq:q p def thru a a}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 is a complex-valued function that replaces 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\omega t}$
\end_inset 

, while the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 are time-independent.
 The present task is to choose the function 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 and the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 in an appropriate way.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 the 
\series bold 
mode function
\series default 
 because we shall later apply the same decomposition to modes of a quantum
 field.
\layout Standard

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}(t)$
\end_inset 

 must be a solution of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:osc var omega}

\end_inset 

), we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 must satisfy the same equation,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ddot{v}+\omega^{2}(t)v=0.\label{eq:v mode fun equ 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Furthermore, the canonical commutation relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\hat{q}(t),\hat{p}(t)\right]=i$
\end_inset 

 entails
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\hat{a}^{-},\hat{a}^{+}\right]=\frac{2i}{\dot{v}v^{*}-\dot{v}^{*}v}.\]

\end_inset 

Note that the expression 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\dot{v}v^{*}-\dot{v}^{*}v\equiv W[v,v^{*}]\]

\end_inset 

 is the Wronskian of the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{*}(t)$
\end_inset 

, and it is well known that 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset 

.
 We may therefore normalize the mode function 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
W[v,v^{*}]=\dot{v}v^{*}-\dot{v}^{*}v=2i,\label{eq:v v normalization}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

which will yield the standard commutation relations for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\hat{a}^{-},\hat{a}^{+}\right]=1.\]

\end_inset 

 We can then postulate the existence of the ground state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}^{-}\left|0\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset 

.
 Excited states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 (
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,...$
\end_inset 

) are defined in the standard way by Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:excited state def}

\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

With the normalization\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:v v normalization}

\end_inset 

), the creation and annihilation operators are expressed through the canonical
