 Properties of mode functions
\layout Standard

Here is a summary of some elementary properties of a time-dependent oscillator
 equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ddot{x}+\omega^{2}(t)x=0.\label{eq:osc td equ}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

This equation has a two-dimensional space of solutions.
 Any two linearly independent solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(t)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(t)$
\end_inset 

 are a basis in that space.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula \[
W\left[x_{1},x_{2}\right]\equiv\dot{x}_{1}x_{2}-x_{1}\dot{x}_{2}\]

\end_inset 

 is called the 
\series bold 
Wronskian
\series default 
 of the two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(t)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(t)$
\end_inset 

.
 It is easy to see that the Wronskian 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left[x_{1},x_{2}\right]$
\end_inset 

 is time-independent if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1,2}(t)$
\end_inset 

 satisfy Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:osc td equ}

\end_inset 

).
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left[x_{1},x_{2}\right]\neq0$
\end_inset 

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(t)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(t)$
\end_inset 

 are two linearly independent solutions.
 
\layout Standard

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1}(t),x_{2}(t)\right\} $
\end_inset 

 is a basis of solutions, it is convenient to define the complex function
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)\equiv x_{1}(t)+ix_{2}(t)$
\end_inset 

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{*}(t)$
\end_inset 

 are linearly independent and form a basis in the space of 
\emph on 
complex
\emph default 
 solutions of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:osc td equ}

\end_inset 

).
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\textrm{Im}(\dot{v}v^{*})=\frac{\dot{v}v^{*}-\dot{v}^{*}v}{2i}=\frac{1}{2i}W\left[v,v^{*}\right]=-W\left[x_{1},x_{2}\right]\neq0,\]

\end_inset 

 and thus the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}(\dot{v}v^{*})$
\end_inset 

 is a nonzero real constant.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 is multiplied by a constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)\rightarrow\lambda v(t)$
\end_inset 

, the Wronskian 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left[v,v^{*}\right]$
\end_inset 

 changes by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|^{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore we may normalize 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 to a prescribed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}(\dot{v}v^{*})$
\end_inset 

 by choosing the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset 

, as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{*}$
\end_inset 

 are linearly independent solutions so that 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left[v,v^{*}\right]\neq0$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

A complex solution 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:osc td equ}

\end_inset 

) is an admissible mode function if 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 is normalized by the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}(\dot{v}v^{*})=1$
\end_inset 

.
 It follows that any solution 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 normalized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}(\dot{v}v^{*})=1$
\end_inset 

 is necessarily complex-valued and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(t)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{*}(t)$
\end_inset 

 are a basis of linearly independent complex solutions of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:osc td equ}

\end_inset 

).
 
