\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Relationship-between-in}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n_{\textrm{out}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0,1,2,...$
\end_inset 

, form a complete basis in the Hilbert space of the harmonic oscillator.
 However, the set of states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n_{\textrm{in}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is another complete basis in the same space.
 Therefore the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{\textrm{in}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 must be expressible as a linear combination of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 states,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|0_{\textrm{in}}\right\rangle =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\Lambda_{n}\left|n_{\textrm{out}}\right\rangle ,\label{eq:0in through out}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are suitable coefficients.
 If the mode functions are related by a Bogolyubov transformation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:bogo v v}

\end_inset 

), one can show that these coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Lambda_{2n}=\left[1-\left|\frac{\beta}{\alpha}\right|^{2}\right]^{1/4}\left(\frac{\beta}{\alpha}\right)^{n}\sqrt{\frac{(2n-1)!!}{(2n)!!}},\quad\Lambda_{2n+1}=0.\label{eq:Lambda b a def}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The relation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:0in through out}

\end_inset 

) shows that the early-time ground state is a superposition of excited states
 at late times, having the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Lambda_{n}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset 

 for the occupation number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

.
 We thus conclude that the presence of an external influence leads to excitation
s of the oscillator.
 (Later on, when we consider field theory, such excitations will be interpreted
 as particle production.) In the present case, the influence of external
 forces on the oscillator consists of the changing frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(t)$
\end_inset 

, which is formally a parameter of the Lagrangian.
 For this reason, the excitations arising in a time-dependent oscillator
 are called 
\series bold 
parametric excitations
\series default 
.
\layout Standard

Finally, let us compute the expected particle number in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 regime, assuming that the oscillator is in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{\textrm{in}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 The expectation value of the number operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}_{\textrm{out}}\equiv\hat{a}_{\textrm{out}}^{+}\hat{a}_{\textrm{out}}^{-}$
\end_inset 

 in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{\textrm{in}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is easily found using Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:aout thru ain}

\end_inset 

):
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\langle 0_{\textrm{in}}\right|\hat{a}_{\textrm{out}}^{+}\hat{a}_{\textrm{out}}^{-}\left|0_{\textrm{in}}\right\rangle =\left\langle 0_{\textrm{in}}\right|\left(\alpha\hat{a}_{\textrm{in}}^{+}+\beta^{*}\hat{a}_{\textrm{in}}^{-}\right)\left(\alpha^{*}\hat{a}_{\textrm{in}}^{-}+\beta\hat{a}_{\textrm{in}}^{+}\right)\left|0_{\textrm{in}}\right\rangle =\left|\beta\right|^{2}.\]

\end_inset 

Therefore, a nonzero coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 signifies the presence of particles in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 region.
