\series default 
 
\layout Standard

In order to find the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{n}$
\end_inset 

, we need to solve the equation
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=\hat{a}_{\textrm{in}}^{-}\left|0_{\textrm{in}}\right\rangle =\left(\alpha\hat{a}_{\textrm{out}}^{-}-\beta\hat{a}_{\textrm{out}}^{+}\right)\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\Lambda_{n}\left|n_{\textrm{out}}\right\rangle .\]

\end_inset 

Using the known properties
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{a}^{+}\left|n\right\rangle =\sqrt{n+1}\left|n+1\right\rangle ,\quad\hat{a}^{-}\left|n\right\rangle =\sqrt{n}\left|n-1\right\rangle ,\]

\end_inset 

we obtain the recurrence relation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Lambda_{n+2}=\Lambda_{n}\frac{\beta}{\alpha}\sqrt{\frac{n+1}{n+2}};\quad\Lambda_{1}=0.\]

\end_inset 

Therefore, only even-numbered 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{2n}$
\end_inset 

 are nonzero and may be expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{0}$
\end_inset 

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Lambda_{2n}=\Lambda_{0}\left(\frac{\beta}{\alpha}\right)^{n}\sqrt{\frac{1\cdot3\cdot...\cdot(2n-1)}{2\cdot4\cdot...\cdot(2n)}}\equiv\Lambda_{0}\left(\frac{\beta}{\alpha}\right)^{n}\sqrt{\frac{(2n-1)!!}{(2n)!!}},\quad n\geq1.\]

\end_inset 

For convenience, one defines 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-1\right)!!=1$
\end_inset 

, so the above expression remains valid also for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is determined from the normalization condition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle 0_{\textrm{in}}\right|0_{\textrm{in}}\rangle=1$
\end_inset 

, which can be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\Lambda_{0}\right|^{2}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left|\frac{\beta}{\alpha}\right|^{2n}\frac{(2n-1)!!}{(2n)!!}=1.\]

\end_inset 

The infinite sum can be evaluated as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset 

 be an auxiliary function defined by the series
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(z)\equiv\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}z^{2n}\frac{(2n-1)!!}{(2n)!!}.\]

\end_inset 

At this point one can guess that this is a Taylor expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=\left(1-z^{2}\right)^{-1/2}$
\end_inset 

; then one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{0}=1/\sqrt{f(z)}$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $z\equiv\left|\beta/\alpha\right|$
\end_inset 

.
 If we would like to avoid guessing, we could manipulate the above series
 in order to derive a differential equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
f(z) & =1+\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}z^{2n}\frac{2n-1}{2n}\frac{(2n-3)!!}{(2n-2)!!}=1+\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}z^{2n}\frac{(2n-3)!!}{(2n-2)!!}-\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{z^{2n}}{2n}\frac{(2n-3)!!}{(2n-2)!!}\\
 & =1+z^{2}f(z)-\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{z^{2n}}{2n}\frac{(2n-3)!!}{(2n-2)!!}.\end{align*}

\end_inset 

Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $d/dz$
\end_inset 

 of both parts, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{dz}\left[1+z^{2}f(z)-f(z)\right]=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}z^{2n-1}\frac{(2n-3)!!}{(2n-2)!!}=zf(z),\]

\end_inset 

hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset 

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d}{dz}\left[(z^{2}-1)f(z)\right]=\left(z^{2}-1\right)\frac{df}{dz}+2zf(z)=zf(z);\quad f(0)=1.\]

\end_inset 

The solution is
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(z)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-z^{2}}}.\]

\end_inset 

Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $z\equiv\left|\beta/\alpha\right|$
\end_inset 

, we obtain the required result,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Lambda_{0}=\left[1-\left|\frac{\beta}{\alpha}\right|^{2}\right]^{1/4}.\]

\end_inset 


