\layout Subsection

Quantum-mechanical analogy 
\layout Standard

The time-dependent oscillator equation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:osc td equ}

\end_inset 

) is formally similar to the stationary Schrödinger equation for the wave
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)$
\end_inset 

 of a quantum particle in a one-dimensional potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x)$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{d^{2}\psi}{dx^{2}}+\left(E-V(x)\right)\psi=0.\]

\end_inset 

The two equations are related by the replacements 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow x$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{2}(t)\rightarrow E-V(x)$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

To illustrate the analogy, let us consider the case when the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x)$
\end_inset 

 is almost constant for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<x_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>x_{2}$
\end_inset 

 but varies in the intermediate region (see Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:tun-analogy}

\end_inset 

).
 An incident wave 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)=\exp(-ipx)$
\end_inset 

 comes from large positive 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 and is scattered off the potential.
 A reflected wave 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}(x)=R\exp(ipx)$
\end_inset 

 is produced in the region 
\begin_inset Formula $x>x_{2}$
\end_inset 

 and a transmitted wave 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{T}(x)=T\exp(-ipx)$
\end_inset 

 in the region 
\begin_inset Formula $x<x_{1}$
\end_inset 

.
 For most potentials, the reflection amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset 

 is nonzero.
 The conservation of probability gives the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|R\right|^{2}+\left|T\right|^{2}=1$
\end_inset 

.
