\layout Section

Scalar field in expanding universe
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:chapter06}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Let us now turn to the situation when quantum fields are influenced by strong
 gravitational fields.
 In this chapter, we use units where 
\begin_inset Formula $c=G=1$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset 

 is Newton's constant.
\layout Subsection

Curved spacetime 
\layout Standard

Einstein's theory of gravitation (
\series bold 
General Relativity
\series default 
) is based on the notion of 
\series bold 
curved spacetime
\series default 
, i.e.\SpecialChar ~
a manifold with arbitrary coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x\equiv\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset 

 and a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}(x)$
\end_inset 

 which replaces the flat Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset 

.
 The metric defines the 
\series bold 
interval
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
ds^{2}=g_{\mu\nu}dx^{\mu}dx^{\nu},\]

\end_inset 

which describes physically measured lengths and times.
 According to the Einstein equation, the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}(x)$
\end_inset 

 is determined by the distribution of matter in the entire universe.
\layout Standard

Here are some basic examples of spacetimes.
 In the absence of matter, the metric is equal to the Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mu\nu}=\textrm{diag}\left(1,-1,-1,-1\right)$
\end_inset 

 (in Cartesian coordinates).
 In the presence of a single black hole of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset 

, the metric can be written in spherical coordinates as
\begin_inset Formula \[
ds^{2}=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)dt^{2}-\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{-1}dr^{2}-r^{2}\left[d\theta^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta d\phi^{2}\right].\]

\end_inset 

Finally, a certain class of spatially homogeneous and isotropic distributions
 of matter in the universe yields a metric of the form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ds^{2}=dt^{2}-a^{2}(t)\left[dx^{2}+dy^{2}+dy^{2}\right],\label{eq:flat FRW metric}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset 

 is a certain function called the 
\series bold 
scale factor
\series default 
.
 (The interpretation is that 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

scales
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 the flat metric 
\begin_inset Formula $dx^{2}+dy^{2}+dz^{2}$
\end_inset 

 at different times.) Spacetimes with metrics of the form\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:flat FRW metric}

\end_inset 

) are called Friedmann-Robertson-Walker (FRW) spacetimes with flat spatial
 sections (in short, 
\series bold 
flat FRW
\series default 
 spacetimes).
 Note that it is only the 
\emph on 
three-dimensional
\emph default 
 spatial sections which are flat; the four-dimensional geometry of such
 spacetimes is usually curved.
 The class of flat FRW spacetimes is important in cosmology because its
 geometry agrees to a good precision with the present results of astrophysical
 measurements.
\layout Standard

In this course, we shall not be concerned with the task of obtaining the
 metric.
 It will be assumed that a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}(x)$
\end_inset 

 is already known in some coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x^{\mu}\right\} $
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Subsection

Scalar field in cosmological background
\layout Standard

Presently, we shall study the behavior of a quantum field in a flat FRW
 spacetime with the metric\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:flat FRW metric}

\end_inset 

).
 In Einstein's General Relativity, every kind of energy influences the geometry
 of spacetime.
 However, we shall treat the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}(x)$
\end_inset 

 as fixed and disregard the influence of fields on the geometry.
 
\layout Standard

A 
\series bold 
minimally coupled
\series default 
, free, real, massive scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset 

 in a curved spacetime is described by the action
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S=\int\sqrt{-g}d^{4}x\left[\frac{1}{2}g^{\alpha\beta}\left(\partial_{\alpha}\phi\right)\left(\partial_{\beta}\phi\right)-\frac{1}{2}m^{2}\phi^{2}\right].\label{eq:phi min action 3}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

(Note the difference between Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi min action 3}

\end_inset 

) and Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:field rel action}

\end_inset 

): the Minkowski metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset 

 is replaced by the curved metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset 

, and the integration uses the covariant volume element 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}d^{4}x$
\end_inset 

.
 This is the minimal change necessary to make the theory of the scalar field
 compatible with General Relativity.) The equation of motion for the field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

 is derived straightforwardly as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g^{\mu\nu}\partial_{\mu}\partial_{\nu}\phi+\frac{1}{\sqrt{-g}}\left(\partial_{\nu}\phi\right)\partial_{\mu}\left(g^{\mu\nu}\sqrt{-g}\right)+m^{2}\phi=0.\label{eq:phi equ noncov}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

This equation can be rewritten more concisely using the covariant derivative
 corresponding to the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
g^{\mu\nu}\nabla_{\mu}\nabla_{\nu}\phi+m^{2}\phi=0,\]

\end_inset 

which shows explicitly that this is a generalization of the Klein-Gordon
 equation to curved spacetime.
 
\layout Standard

We cannot directly use the quantization technique developed for fields in
 the flat spacetime.
 First, let us carry out a few mathematical transformations to simplify
 the task.
 
\layout Standard

The metric\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:flat FRW metric}

\end_inset 

) for a flat FRW spacetime can be simplified if we replace the coordinate
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 by the 
\series bold 
conformal time
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\eta(t)\equiv\int_{t_{0}}^{t}\frac{dt}{a(t)},\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is an arbitrary constant.
 The scale factor 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset 

 must be expressed through the new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

; let us denote that function again by 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\eta)$
\end_inset 

.
 In the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},\eta\right)$
\end_inset 

, the interval is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ds^{2}=a^{2}(\eta)\left[d\eta^{2}-d\mathbf{x}^{2}\right],\label{eq:metric conf flat}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

so the metric is 
\series bold 
conformally flat
\series default 
 (equal to the flat metric multiplied by a factor): 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}=a^{2}\eta_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\mu\nu}=a^{-2}\eta^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:free fields in gravity}

\end_inset 

Further, it is convenient to introduce the auxiliary field 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi\equiv a(\eta)\phi$
\end_inset 

.
 Then one can show that the action\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi min action 3}

\end_inset 

) can be rewritten in terms of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset 

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S=\frac{1}{2}\int d^{3}\mathbf{x}\, d\eta\left(\chi^{\prime2}-(\nabla\chi)^{2}-m_{\textrm{eff}}^{2}(\eta)\chi^{2}\right),\label{eq:chi action 4}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where the prime 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\prime}$
\end_inset 

 denotes 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial\eta$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\textrm{eff}}$
\end_inset 

 is the time-dependent 
\series bold 
effective mass
\series default 

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
m_{\textrm{eff}}^{2}(\eta)\equiv m^{2}a^{2}-\frac{a^{\prime\prime}}{a}.\label{eq:meff def}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The action\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi action 4}

\end_inset 

) is very similar to the action\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:field rel action}

\end_inset 

), except for the presence of the time-dependent mass.
\layout Standard
