\layout Subsection

Mode expansion
\layout Standard

It follows from the action\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi action 4}

\end_inset 

) that the equation of motion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(\mathbf{x},\eta)$
\end_inset 

 is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\chi^{\prime\prime}-\Delta\chi+\left(m^{2}a^{2}-\frac{a^{\prime\prime}}{a}\right)\chi=0.\label{eq:v equ of motion}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Expanding the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset 

 in Fourier modes,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\chi\left(\mathbf{x},\eta\right)=\int\frac{d^{3}\mathbf{k}}{(2\pi)^{3/2}}\chi_{\mathbf{k}}(\eta)e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{x}},\label{eq:chi modes 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 we obtain from Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:v equ of motion}

\end_inset 

) the decoupled equations of motion for the modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\chi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\prime\prime}+\left[k^{2}+m^{2}a^{2}(\eta)-\frac{a^{\prime\prime}}{a}\right]\chi_{\mathbf{k}}\equiv\chi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\prime\prime}+\omega_{k}^{2}(\eta)\chi_{\mathbf{k}}=0.\label{eq:vk equ motion}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

All the modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 with equal 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{k}\right|=k$
\end_inset 

 are complex solutions of the same equation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:vk equ motion}

\end_inset 

).
 This equation describes a harmonic oscillator with a time-dependent frequency.
 Therefore, we may apply the techniques we developed in chapter\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Oscillator-with-varying}

\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

We begin by choosing a mode function 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

, which is a complex-valued solution of 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{k}^{\prime\prime}+\omega_{k}^{2}(\eta)v_{k}=0,\quad\omega_{k}^{2}(\eta)\equiv k^{2}+m_{\textrm{eff}}^{2}(\eta).\label{eq:mode func equs}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Then, the general solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 is expressed as a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}^{*}$
\end_inset 

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\chi_{\mathbf{k}}(\eta)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left[a_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}v_{k}^{*}(\eta)+a_{-\mathbf{k}}^{+}v_{k}(\eta)\right],\label{eq:chi through v}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 are complex constants of integration that depend on the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

 (but not on 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

).
 The index 
\begin_inset Formula $-\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

 in the second term of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi through v}

\end_inset 

) and the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset 

 are chosen for later convenience.
 
\layout Standard

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset 

 is real, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}^{*}=\chi_{-\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

.
 It follows from Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi through v}

\end_inset 

) that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathbf{k}}^{+}=\left(a_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}\right)^{*}$
\end_inset 

.
 Combining Eqs.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi modes 1}

\end_inset 

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi through v}

\end_inset 

), we find 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\chi\left(\mathbf{x},\eta\right) & =\int\frac{d^{3}\mathbf{k}}{(2\pi)^{3/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left[a_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}v_{k}^{*}(\eta)+a_{-\mathbf{k}}^{+}v_{k}(\eta)\right]e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{x}}\nonumber \\
 & =\int\frac{d^{3}\mathbf{k}}{(2\pi)^{3/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left[a_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}v_{k}^{*}(\eta)e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{x}}+a_{\mathbf{k}}^{+}v_{k}(\eta)e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{x}}\right].\label{eq:chi cl mode exp}\end{align}

\end_inset 

 Note that the integration variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

 was changed (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\rightarrow-\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

) in the second term of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi cl mode exp}

\end_inset 

) to make the integrand a manifestly real expression.
 (This is done only for convenience.)
\layout Standard

The relation (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi cl mode exp}

\end_inset 

) is called the 
\series bold 
mode expansion
\series default 
 of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi\left(\mathbf{x},\eta\right)$
\end_inset 

 w.r.t.\SpecialChar ~
the mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

.
 At this point the choice of the mode functions is still arbitrary.
\layout Standard

The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 are easily expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

: 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Bogolyubov coefficients!finding}

\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}=\sqrt{2}\frac{v_{k}^{\prime}\chi_{\mathbf{k}}-v_{k}\chi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\prime}}{v_{k}^{\prime}v_{k}^{*}-v_{k}v_{k}^{*\prime}}=\sqrt{2}\frac{W\left[v_{k},\chi_{\mathbf{k}}\right]}{W\left[v_{k},v_{k}^{*}\right]};\quad a_{\mathbf{k}}^{+}=\left(a_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}\right)^{*}.\label{eq:ak through chi v}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Note that the numerators and denominators in Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ak through chi v}

\end_inset 

) are time-independent since they are Wronskians of solutions of the same
 oscillator equation.
 
\layout Subsection

Quantization of scalar field 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Quantization-of-scalar1}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The field 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(x)$
\end_inset 

 can be quantized directly through the mode expansion\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi cl mode exp}

\end_inset 

), which can be used for quantum fields in the same way as for classical
 fields.
 The mode expansion for the field operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}$
\end_inset 

 is found by replacing the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 in Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi cl mode exp}

\end_inset 

) by time-independent operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\chi}\left(\mathbf{x},\eta\right)=\int\frac{d^{3}\mathbf{k}}{(2\pi)^{3/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{x}}v_{k}^{*}(\eta)\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}+e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{x}}v_{k}(\eta)\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{+}\right),\label{eq:chi mode exp 2}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 are mode functions obeying Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:mode func equs}

\end_inset 

).
 The operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 satisfy the usual commutation relations for creation and annihilation operators
,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{-},\,\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}'}^{+}\right]=\delta(\mathbf{k}-\mathbf{k}'),\quad\left[\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{-},\,\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}'}^{-}\right]=\left[\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{+},\,\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}'}^{+}\right]=0.\label{eq:ak ak comm 2}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The commutation relations (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ak ak comm 2}

\end_inset 

) are consistent with the canonical relations 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\chi(\mathbf{x}_{1},\eta),\chi^{\prime}(\mathbf{x}_{2},\eta)\right]=i\delta(\mathbf{x}_{1}-\mathbf{x}_{2})\]

\end_inset 

 only if the mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 are normalized by the condition
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\textrm{Im}\left(v_{k}^{\prime}v_{k}^{*}\right)=\frac{v_{k}^{\prime}v_{k}^{*}-v_{k}v_{k}^{\prime*}}{2i}\equiv\frac{W\left[v_{k},v_{k}^{*}\right]}{2i}=1.\label{eq:normalization of v}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Therefore, quantization of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}$
\end_inset 

 can be accomplished by postulating the mode expansion\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi mode exp 2}

\end_inset 

), the commutation relations\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ak ak comm 2}

\end_inset 

) and the normalization\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:normalization of v}

\end_inset 

).
 The choice of the mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 will be made later on.
\layout Standard

The mode expansion (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi mode exp 2}

\end_inset 

) can be visualized as the general solution of the field equation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:v equ of motion}

\end_inset 

), where the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 are integration constants.
 The mode expansion can also be viewed as a 
\emph on 
definition
\emph default 
 of the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 through the field operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}\left(\mathbf{x},\eta\right)$
\end_inset 

.
 Explicit formulae relating 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}\equiv\hat{\chi}^{\prime}$
\end_inset 

 are analogous to Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ak through chi v}

\end_inset 

).
 Clearly, the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 depends on the choice of the mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Subsection

Vacuum state and particle states 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Definition-of-particles}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Once the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 are determined, the vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is defined as the eigenstate of all annihilation operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}$
\end_inset 

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset 

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}\left|0\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset 

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

.
 An excited state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|m_{\mathbf{k}_{1}},n_{\mathbf{k}_{2}},...\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 with the occupation numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n,...$
\end_inset 

 in the modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}_{1}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}_{2}}$
\end_inset 

, ..., is constructed by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|m_{\mathbf{k}_{1}},n_{\mathbf{k}_{2}},...\right\rangle \equiv\frac{1}{\sqrt{m!n!...}}\left[\left(\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}_{1}}^{+}\right)^{m}\left(\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}_{2}}^{+}\right)^{n}...\right]\left|0\right\rangle .\label{eq:m n particle state 0}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{\mathbf{k}_{1}},0_{\mathbf{k}_{2}},...\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 for brevity.
 An arbitrary quantum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is a linear combination of these states,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\psi\right\rangle =\sum_{m,n,...}C_{mn...}\left|m_{\mathbf{k}_{1}},n_{\mathbf{k}_{2}},...\right\rangle .\]

\end_inset 

If the field is in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, the probability for measuring the occupation number 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset 

 in the mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}_{1}}$
\end_inset 

, the number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 in the mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}_{2}}$
\end_inset 

, etc., is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|C_{mn...}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Let us now comment on the role of the mode functions.
 Complex solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 of a second-order differential equation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:mode func equs}

\end_inset 

) with one normalization condition\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:normalization of v}

\end_inset 

) are parametrized by one complex parameter.
 Multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 by a constant phase 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\alpha}$
\end_inset 

 introduces an extra phase 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\pm i\alpha}$
\end_inset 

 in the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{k}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

, which can be compensated by a constant phase factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\alpha}$
\end_inset 

 in the state vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|m_{\mathbf{k}_{1}},n_{\mathbf{k}_{2}},...\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 There remains one real free parameter that distinguishes physically inequivalen
t mode functions.
 With each possible choice of the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

, the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 and consequently the vacuum state and particle states are different.
 As long as the mode functions satisfy Eqs.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:mode func equs}

\end_inset 

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:normalization of v}

\end_inset 

), the commutation relations\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ak ak comm 2}

\end_inset 

) hold and thus the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 formally resemble the creation and annihilation operators for particle
 states.
 However, we do not yet know whether the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 obtained with some choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 actually correspond to physical particles and whether the quantum state
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 describes the physical vacuum.
 The correct commutation relations alone do not guarantee the validity of
 the physical interpretation of the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 and of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 For this interpretation to be valid, the mode functions must be 
\emph on 
appropriately
\emph default 
 
\emph on 
selected
\emph default 
; we postpone the consideration of this important issue until Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:choice of vacuum}

\end_inset 

 below.
 For now, we shall formally study the consequences of choosing several sets
 of mode functions to quantize the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

.
 
