- and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particles remains unspecified.
 Later on, we shall apply this formalism to study specific physical effects
 and the interpretation of excited states corresponding to various mode
 functions will be explained.
 At this point, let us only remark that the 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-vacuum is in general a superposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

-states, similarly to what we found in Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Relationship-between-in}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Subsection

Mean particle number
\layout Standard

Let us calculate the mean number of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particles of the mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

-vacuum state.
 The expectation value of the 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particle number operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}_{\mathbf{k}}^{(b)}=\hat{b}_{\mathbf{k}}^{+}\hat{b}_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}$
\end_inset 

 in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|_{(a)}0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is found using Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:bk ak Bogo}

\end_inset 

):
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\left\langle _{(a)}0\right|\hat{N}^{(b)}\left|_{(a)}0\right\rangle  & =\left\langle _{(a)}0\right|\hat{b}_{\mathbf{k}}^{+}\hat{b}_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}\left|_{(a)}0\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & =\left\langle _{(a)}0\right|\left(\alpha_{k}^{*}\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{+}+\beta_{k}\hat{a}_{-\mathbf{k}}^{-}\right)\left(\alpha_{k}\hat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{-}+\beta_{k}^{*}\hat{a}_{-\mathbf{k}}^{+}\right)\left|_{(a)}0\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & =\left\langle _{(a)}0\right|\left(\beta_{k}\hat{a}_{-\mathbf{k}}^{-}\right)\left(\beta_{k}^{*}\hat{a}_{-\mathbf{k}}^{+}\right)\left|_{(a)}0\right\rangle =\left|\beta_{k}\right|^{2}\delta^{(3)}(0).\label{eq:Energy beta k}\end{align}

\end_inset 

The divergent factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{(3)}(0)$
\end_inset 

 is a consequence of considering an infinite spatial volume.
 This divergent factor would be replaced by the box volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset 

 if we quantized the field in a finite box.
 Therefore we can divide by this factor and obtain the mean 
\emph on 
density
\emph default 
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particles in the mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
n_{k}=\left|\beta_{k}\right|^{2}.\label{eq:density beta k}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The Bogolyubov coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}$
\end_inset 

 is dimensionless and the density 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{k}$
\end_inset 

 is the mean number of particles per spatial volume 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{3}\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset 

 and per wave number 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{3}\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int n_{k}d^{3}\mathbf{k}\, d^{3}\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset 

 is the (dimensionless) total mean number of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particles in the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

-vacuum state.
\layout Standard

The combined mean density of particles in all modes is 
\begin_inset Formula $\int d^{3}\mathbf{k}\left|\beta_{k}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 Note that this integral might diverge, which would indicate that one cannot
 disregard the backreaction of the produced particles on other fields and
 on the metric.
\layout Subsection

Instantaneous lowest-energy vacuum
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:choice of vacuum}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

In the theory developed so far, the particle interpretation depends on the
 choice of the mode functions.
 For instance, the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

-vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|_{(a)}0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 defined above is a state without 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

-particles but with 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particle density 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{k}$
\end_inset 

 in each mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

.
 A natural question to ask is whether the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

-particles or the 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particles are the correct representation of the observable particles.
 The problem at hand is to determine the mode functions that describe the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

actual
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 physical vacuum and particles.
\layout Standard

Previously, we defined the vacuum state as the eigenstate with the lowest
 energy.
 However, in the present case the Hamiltonian explicitly depends on time
 and thus does not have time-independent eigenstates that could serve as
 vacuum states.
 
\layout Standard

One possible prescription for the vacuum state is to select a particular
 moment of time, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

, and to define the vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|_{\eta_{0}}0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 as the lowest-energy eigenstate of the 
\emph on 
instantaneous
\emph default 
 Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}(\eta_{0})$
\end_inset 

.
 To obtain the mode functions that describe the vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|_{\eta_{0}}0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, we first compute the expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle _{(v)}0\right|\hat{H}(\eta_{0})\left|_{(v)}0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 in the vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|_{(v)}0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 determined by arbitrarily chosen mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

.
 Then we can minimize that expectation value with respect to all possible
 choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

.
 (A standard result in linear algebra is that the minimization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x\right|\hat{A}\left|x\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 with respect to all normalized vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is equivalent to finding the eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

 with the smallest eigenvalue.) This computation is analogous to that of
 Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Choice-of-the}

\end_inset 

, and the result is similar to Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:v good init cond}

\end_inset 

): If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}^{2}(\eta_{0})>0$
\end_inset 

, the required initial conditions for the mode functions are 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{k}\left(\eta_{0}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\omega_{k}(\eta_{0})}},\quad v_{k}^{\prime}(\eta_{0})=i\sqrt{\omega_{k}(\eta_{0})}=i\omega_{k}v_{k}(\eta_{0}).\label{eq:inst energy vac}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}^{2}(\eta_{0})<0$
\end_inset 

, the instantaneous lowest-energy vacuum state does not exist.
\layout Standard

For a scalar field in the Minkowski spacetime, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}$
\end_inset 

 is time-independent and the prescription\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:inst energy vac}

\end_inset 

) yields the standard mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula \[
v_{k}(\eta)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\omega_{k}}}e^{i\omega_{k}\eta},\]

\end_inset 

 which remain the vacuum mode functions at all times.
 But this is not the case for a time-dependent gravitational background,
 because then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}(\eta)\neq\textrm{const}$
\end_inset 

 and the mode function selected by the initial conditions (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:inst energy vac}

\end_inset 

) imposed at a time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

 will generally differ from the mode function selected at another time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\neq\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
 In other words, the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|_{\eta_{0}}0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is not an energy eigenstate at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset 

.
 In fact, one can show that there are no states which remain instantaneous
 eigenstates of the Hamiltonian at all times.
 
\layout Subsection

Computation of Bogolyubov coefficients
\layout Standard

Computations of Bogolyubov coefficients requires knowledge of solutions
 of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:mode func equs}

\end_inset 

), which is an equation of a harmonic oscillator with a time-dependent frequency
, with specified initial conditions.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 are mode functions describing instantaneous lowest-energy states defined
 at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\eta_{1}$
\end_inset 

.
 To determine the Bogolyubov coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}$
\end_inset 

 connecting these mode functions, it is necessary to know the functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 and their derivatives at 
\emph on 
only
\emph default 
 
\emph on 
one
\emph default 
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

, e.g.\SpecialChar ~
at 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
 From Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:uk vk Bogo}

\end_inset 

) and its derivative at 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
v_{k}^{*}\left(\eta_{0}\right)=\alpha_{k}u_{k}^{*}\left(\eta_{0}\right)+\beta_{k}u_{k}\left(\eta_{0}\right),\\
v_{k}^{*\prime}\left(\eta_{0}\right)=\alpha_{k}u_{k}^{*\prime}\left(\eta_{0}\right)+\beta_{k}u_{k}^{\prime}\left(\eta_{0}\right).\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

This system of equations can be solved for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}$
\end_inset 

 using Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:normalization of v}

\end_inset 

):
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\alpha_{k}=\left.\frac{u_{k}^{\prime}v_{k}^{*}-u_{k}v_{k}^{*\prime}}{2i}\right|_{\eta_{0}},\quad\beta_{k}^{*}=\left.\frac{u_{k}^{\prime}v_{k}-u_{k}v_{k}^{\prime}}{2i}\right|_{\eta_{0}}.\label{eq:computing Bogo}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

These relations hold at any time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

 (note that the numerators are Wronskians and thus are time-independent).
 For instance, knowing only the asymptotics of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset 

 would suffice to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

A well-known method to obtain an approximate solution of equations of the
 type\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:mode func equs}

\end_inset 

) is the 
\series bold 
WKB approximation
\series default 
, which gives the approximate solution satisfying the condition\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:inst energy vac}

\end_inset 

) at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{k}(\eta)\approx\frac{1}{\sqrt{\omega_{k}(\eta)}}\exp\left[i\int_{\eta_{0}}^{\eta}\omega_{k}(\eta_{1})d\eta_{1}\right].\label{eq:WKB approx v}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

However, it is straightforward to see that the approximation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:WKB approx v}

\end_inset 

) satisfies the instantaneous minimum-energy condition at every other time
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\neq\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

 as well.
 In other words, within the WKB approximation, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k}(\eta)\approx v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, if we use the WKB approximation to compute the Bogolyubov coefficien
t between instantaneous vacuum states, we shall obtain the incorrect result
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}=0$
\end_inset 

.
 The WKB approximation is insufficiently precise to capture the difference
 between the instantaneous vacuum states defined at different times.
\layout Standard

One can use the following method to obtain a better approximation to the
 mode function 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

.
 Let us focus attention on one mode and drop the index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

.
 Introduce a new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
v(\eta)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\omega(\eta_{0})}}\exp\left[i\int_{\eta_{0}}^{\eta}\omega(\eta_{1})d\eta_{1}+\int_{\eta_{0}}^{\eta}Z(\eta_{1})d\eta_{1}\right];\quad\frac{v^{\prime}}{v}=i\omega(\eta)+Z(\eta).\]

\end_inset 

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 is a slow-changing function, then we expect that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 is everywhere approximately equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{\omega}}\exp\left[i\int^{\eta}\omega(\eta)d\eta\right]$
\end_inset 

 and the function 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 under the exponential is a small correction; in particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(\eta_{0})=0$
\end_inset 

 at the time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
 It is straightforward to derive the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 from Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:mode func equs}

\end_inset 

),
\begin_inset Formula \[
Z'+2i\omega Z=-i\omega^{\prime}-Z^{2}.\]

\end_inset 

This equation can be solved using perturbation theory by treating 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{2}$
\end_inset 

 as a small perturbation.
 To obtain the first approximation, we disregard 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{2}$
\end_inset 

 and straightforwardly solve the resulting linear equation, which yields
\begin_inset Formula \[
Z_{(1)}(\eta)=-i\int_{\eta_{0}}^{\eta}d\eta_{1}\omega^{\prime}(\eta_{1})\exp\left[-2i\int_{\eta_{1}}^{\eta}\omega(\eta_{2})d\eta_{2}\right].\]

\end_inset 

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{(1)}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 is an integral of a slow-changing function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega'(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 multiplied by a quickly oscillating function and is therefore small, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|Z\right|\ll\omega$
\end_inset 

.
 The first approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{(1)}$
\end_inset 

 is sufficiently precise in most cases.
 The resulting 
\emph on 
approximate
\emph default 
 mode function is
\begin_inset Formula \[
v(\eta)\approx\frac{1}{\sqrt{\omega(\eta_{0})}}\exp\left[i\int_{\eta_{0}}^{\eta}\omega(\eta_{1})d\eta_{1}+\int_{\eta_{0}}^{\eta}Z_{(1)}(\eta)d\eta\right].\]

\end_inset 

The Bogolyubov coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 between instantaneous lowest-energy states defined at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset 

 can be approximately computed using Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:computing Bogo}

\end_inset 

):
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
u(\eta_{1}) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{\omega(\eta_{1})}};\quad u'(\eta_{1})=i\omega(\eta_{1})u(\eta_{1});\\
\beta^{*} & =\frac{1}{2i\sqrt{\omega(\eta_{1})}}\left[i\omega(\eta_{1})v(\eta_{1})-v'(\eta_{1})\right]=v(\eta_{1})\frac{\left(i\omega-\frac{v'}{v}\right)_{\eta_{1}}}{2i\sqrt{\omega(\eta_{1})}}\approx-\frac{v(\eta_{1})Z(\eta_{1})}{2i\sqrt{\omega(\eta_{1})}}.\end{align*}

\end_inset 

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\eta_{1})$
\end_inset 

 is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{-1/2}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|Z\right|\ll\omega$
\end_inset 

, the number of particles is small: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\beta\right|^{2}\ll1$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Section

Amplitude of quantum fluctuations
\layout Standard

In the previous chapter the focus was on particle production.
 The main observable of interest was the average particle number 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\hat{N}\rangle$
\end_inset 

.
 Now we consider another important quantity---the amplitude of field fluctuation
s.
 
\layout Subsection

Fluctuations of averaged fields
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Fluctuations-of-smoothed}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The value of a field cannot be observed at a mathematical point in space.
 Realistic devices can only measure the value of the field averaged over
 some region of space.
 Spatial averages are also the relevant quantity in cosmology because structure
 formation in the universe is explained by fluctuations occurring over large
 regions, e.g.\SpecialChar ~
of galaxy size.
 Therefore, let us consider values of fields averaged over a spatial domain.
\layout Standard

A convenient way to describe spatial averaging over arbitrary domains is
 by using window functions.
 A 
\series bold 
window function
\series default 
 for scale 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

 is any function 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset 

 which is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}\right|\lesssim L$
\end_inset 

, rapidly decays for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}\right|\gg L$
\end_inset 

, and satisfies the normalization condition 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int W\left(\mathbf{x}\right)d^{3}\mathbf{x}=1.\label{eq:window norm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 A typical example of a window function is the 
\series bold 
spherical Gaussian 
\series default 
window
\begin_inset Formula \[
W_{L}\left(\mathbf{x}\right)=\frac{1}{(2\pi)^{3/2}L^{3}}\exp\left[-\frac{\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{2}}{2L^{2}}\right],\]

\end_inset 

which selects 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}\right|\lesssim L$
\end_inset 

.
 This window can be used to describe measurements performed by a device
 that cannot resolve distances smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

We define the 
\series bold 
averaged field
\series default 
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}_{L}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 by integrating the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}(\mathbf{x},\eta)$
\end_inset 

 with a window function that selects the scale 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\chi}_{L}(\eta)\equiv\int d^{3}\mathbf{x}\,\hat{\chi}\left(\mathbf{x},\eta\right)W_{L}(\mathbf{x}),\]

\end_inset 

where we used the Gaussian window (although the final result will not depend
 on this choice).
 The amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\chi_{L}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 of fluctuations in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}_{L}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 in a quantum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is found from
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta\chi_{L}^{2}(\eta)\equiv\left\langle \psi\right|\left[\hat{\chi}_{L}(\eta)\right]^{2}\left|\psi\right\rangle .\]

\end_inset 

For simplicity, we consider the vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 Then the amplitude of vacuum fluctuations in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}_{L}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 can be computed as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

.
 We use the mode expansion\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi mode exp 2}

\end_inset 

) for the field operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}(\mathbf{x},\eta)$
\end_inset 

, assuming that the mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 are given.
 After some straightforward algebra we find
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\langle 0\right|\left[\int d^{3}\mathbf{x}\, W_{L}(\mathbf{x})\hat{\chi}\left(\mathbf{x},\eta\right)\right]^{2}\left|0\right\rangle =\frac{1}{2}\int\frac{d^{3}\mathbf{k}}{(2\pi)^{3}}\left|v_{k}\right|^{2}e^{-k^{2}L^{2}}.\]

\end_inset 

Since the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-k^{2}L^{2}}$
\end_inset 

 is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{k}\right|\lesssim L^{-1}$
\end_inset 

 and almost zero for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{k}\right|\gtrsim L^{-1}$
\end_inset 

, we can estimate the above integral as follows,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{2}\int\frac{d^{3}\mathbf{k}}{(2\pi)^{3}}\left|v_{k}\right|^{2}e^{-k^{2}L^{2}}\sim\int_{0}^{L^{-1}}\! k^{2}\left|v_{k}\right|^{2}dk\sim\left.k^{3}\left|v_{k}\right|^{2}\right|_{k=L^{-1}}.\]

\end_inset 

Thus the amplitude of fluctuations 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\chi_{L}$
\end_inset 

 is (up to a factor of order 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset 

)
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\delta\chi_{L}^{2}\sim k^{3}\left|v_{k}\right|^{2},\;\textrm{where }\, k\sim L^{-1}.\label{eq:delta chi L}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The result\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:delta chi L}

\end_inset 

) is (for 
\emph on 
any
\emph default 
 choice of the window function 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{L}$
\end_inset 

) an order-of-magnitude estimate of the
\series bold 
 amplitude of fluctuations on scale
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

.
 This quantity, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\chi_{L}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

, is defined only up to a factor of order 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset 

 and is a function of time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

 and of the scale 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

.
 Expressed through the wavenumber 
\begin_inset Formula $k\equiv2\pi L^{-1}$
\end_inset 

, the fluctuation amplitude is usually called the 
\series bold 
spectrum of fluctuations
\series default 
.
 
\layout Subsection

Fluctuations in Minkowski spacetime
\layout Standard

Let us now compute the spectrum of fluctuations for a scalar field in the
 Minkowski space.
 
\layout Standard

The vacuum mode functions are 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)=\omega_{k}^{-1/2}\exp\left(i\omega_{k}\eta\right)$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}=\sqrt{k^{2}+m^{2}}$
\end_inset 

.
 Thus, the spectrum of fluctuations in vacuum is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\delta\chi_{L}(\eta)=k^{3/2}\left|v_{k}(\eta)\right|=\frac{k^{3/2}}{\left(k^{2}+m^{2}\right)^{1/4}}.\label{eq:delta chi answer}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

This time-independent spectrum is sketched in Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:sp1}

\end_inset 

.
 When measured with a high-resolution device (small 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

), the field shows large fluctuations.
 On the other hand, if the field is averaged over a large volume (
\begin_inset Formula $L\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset 

), the amplitude of fluctuations tends to zero.
