\layout Subsection

de Sitter spacetime 
\layout Standard

The 
\series bold 
de Sitter spacetime
\series default 
 is used in cosmology to describe periods of accelerated expansion of the
 universe.
 The amplitude of fluctuations is an important quantity to compute in that
 context.
 
\layout Standard

The geometry of the de Sitter spacetime may be specified by a flat FRW metric
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ds^{2}=dt^{2}-a^{2}(t)d\mathbf{x}^{2}\label{eq:ds2 flat}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

with the scale factor 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset 

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a(t)=a_{0}e^{Ht}.\label{eq:de Sitter a}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The 
\series bold 
Hubble parameter
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\dot{a}/a>0$
\end_inset 

 is a fixed constant.
 For convenience, we redefine the origin of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 to set 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=1$
\end_inset 

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)=\exp(Ht)$
\end_inset 

.
 The exponentially growing scale factor describes an accelerating expansion
 (
\series bold 
inflation
\series default 
) of the universe.
\layout Subsubsection*

Horizons
\layout Standard

An important feature of the de Sitter spacetime---the presence of horizons---is
 revealed by the following consideration of trajectories of lightrays.
 A null worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}(t)$
\end_inset 

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}(t)\dot{\mathbf{x}}^{2}(t)=1$
\end_inset 

, which yields the solution 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\mathbf{x}(t)\right|=\frac{1}{H}\left(e^{-Ht_{0}}-e^{-Ht}\right)\]

\end_inset 

 for trajectories starting at the origin, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}(t_{0})=0$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore all lightrays emitted at the origin at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset 

 asymptotically approach the sphere 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\mathbf{x}\right|=r_{\max}(t_{0})\equiv H^{-1}\exp(-Ht_{0})=\left(aH\right)^{-1}.\]

\end_inset 

 This sphere is the 
\series bold 
horizon
\series default 
 for the observer at the origin; the spacetime expands too quickly for lightrays
 to reach any points beyond the horizon.
 Similarly, observers at the origin will never receive any lightrays emitted
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset 

 at points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}\right|>r_{\max}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

It is easy to verify that at any time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset 

 the horizon is always at the same 
\emph on 
proper
\emph default 
 distance 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t_{0})r_{\max}(t_{0})=H^{-1}$
\end_inset 

 from the observer.
 This distance is called the 
\series bold 
horizon scale
\series default 
.
\layout Subsection

Quantum fields in de Sitter spacetime
\layout Standard

To describe a real scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset 

 in the de Sitter spacetime, we first transform the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 to make the metric explicitly conformally flat:
\begin_inset Formula \[
ds^{2}=dt^{2}-a^{2}(t)d\mathbf{x}^{2}=a^{2}(\eta)\left(d\eta^{2}-d\mathbf{x}^{2}\right),\]

\end_inset 

where the conformal time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

 and the scale factor 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 are
\begin_inset Formula \[
\eta=-\frac{1}{H}e^{-Ht},\quad a(\eta)=-\frac{1}{H\eta}.\]

\end_inset 

The conformal time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

 changes from 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset 

 when the proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 goes from 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $+\infty$
\end_inset 

.
 (Since the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

 is always negative, we shall sometimes have to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\eta\right|$
\end_inset 

 in the equations.
 However, it is essential that the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

 grows when 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 grows, so we cannot use 
\begin_inset Formula $-\eta$
\end_inset 

 as the time variable.
 For convenience, we chose the origin of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

 so that the infinite future corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=0$
\end_inset 

.)
\layout Standard

The field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbf{x},\eta)$
\end_inset 

 can now be quantized by the method of Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Quantization-of-scalar}

\end_inset 

.
 We introduce the auxiliary field 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi\equiv a\phi$
\end_inset 

 and use the mode expansion (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:chi mode exp 2}

\end_inset 

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:mode func equs}

\end_inset 

) with
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\omega_{k}^{2}(\eta)=k^{2}+m^{2}a^{2}-\frac{a''}{a}=k^{2}+\left(\frac{m^{2}}{H^{2}}-2\right)\frac{1}{\eta^{2}}.\label{eq:omega k deS}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

From this expression it is clear that the effective frequency may become
 imaginary, i.e.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}^{2}(\eta)<0$
\end_inset 

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{2}<2H^{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 In most cosmological scenarios where the early universe is approximated
 by a region of the de Sitter spacetime, the relevant value of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset 

 is much larger than the masses of elementary particles, i.e.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $m\ll H$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, for simplicity we shall consider the massless field.
\layout Subsection

Bunch-Davies vacuum state
\layout Standard

As we saw before, the vacuum state of a field is determined by the choice
 of mode functions.
 Let us now find the appropriate mode functions for a scalar field in de
 Sitter spacetime.
\layout Standard

With the definition\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:omega k deS}

\end_inset 

) of the effective frequency, where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset 

, Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:mode func equs}

\end_inset 

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{k}^{\prime\prime}+\left(k^{2}-\frac{2}{\eta^{2}}\right)v_{k}=0.\label{eq:vk deSitter equ}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The general solution of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:vk deSitter equ}

\end_inset 

) can be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{k}(\eta)=A_{k}\left(1+\frac{i}{k\eta}\right)e^{ik\eta}+B_{k}\left(1-\frac{i}{k\eta}\right)e^{-ik\eta},\label{eq:A B gen sol v}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}$
\end_inset 

 are constants.
 It is straightforward to check that the normalization of the mode function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}\left(v_{k}^{*}v_{k}^{\prime}\right)=1$
\end_inset 

, constrains the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}$
\end_inset 

 by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|A_{k}\right|^{2}-\left|B_{k}\right|=\frac{1}{k}.\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The constants 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k},B_{k}$
\end_inset 

 determine the mode functions and must be chosen appropriately to obtain
 a physically motivated vacuum state.
 For fields in de Sitter spacetime, there is a preferred vacuum state, which
 is known as the 
\series bold 
Bunch-Davies
\series default 
 (BD) 
\series bold 
vacuum
\series default 
.
 This state is defined essentially as the Minkowski vacuum in the early-time
 limit (
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset 

) of each mode.
 
\layout Standard

Before introducing the BD vacuum, let us consider the prescription of the
 instantaneous vacuum defined at a time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
 If we had 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}^{2}(\eta_{0})>0$
\end_inset 

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

, this prescription would yield a well-defined vacuum state.
 However, there always exists a small enough 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\left|\eta_{0}\right|\ll1$
\end_inset 

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}^{2}(\eta_{0})<0$
\end_inset 

.
 We have seen that the energy in a mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

 cannot be minimized when 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}^{2}<0$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore the instantaneous energy prescription cannot define a vacuum
 state of the entire quantum field (for all modes) but only for the modes
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k\left|\eta_{0}\right|\gtrsim1$
\end_inset 

.
 Note that these are the modes whose wavelength was shorter than the horizon
 length, 
\begin_inset Formula $(aH)^{-1}=\left|\eta_{0}\right|$
\end_inset 

, at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset 

 (i.e.\SpecialChar ~
the 
\series bold 
subhorizon
\series default 
 modes).
\layout Standard

The motivation for introducing the BD vacuum state is the following.
 The effective frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 becomes constant in the early-time limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset 

.
 Physically, this means that the influence of gravity on each mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

 is negligible at sufficiently early (
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

-dependent) times.
 When gravity is negligible, there is a unique vacuum prescription---the
 Minkowski vacuum, which coincides with the instantaneous minimum-energy
 vacuum at all times.
 So it is natural to define the mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 by applying the Minkowski vacuum prescription in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset 

, separately for each mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

.
 This prescription can be expressed by the asymptotic relations
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{k}(\eta)\rightarrow\frac{1}{\sqrt{\omega_{k}}}e^{i\omega_{k}\eta},\quad\frac{v_{k}^{\prime}(\eta)}{v_{k}(\eta)}\rightarrow i\omega_{k},\quad\textrm{ as }\:\eta\rightarrow-\infty.\label{eq:deS adiab vk}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The vacuum state determined by the mode functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 satisfying Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:deS adiab vk}

\end_inset 

) is called the 
\series bold 
Bunch-Davies vacuum
\series default 
.
 It follows that the mode functions of the BD vacuum are given by Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:A B gen sol v}

\end_inset 

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}=1/\sqrt{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}=0$
\end_inset 

, namely
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{k}(\eta)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{k}}\left(1+\frac{i}{k\eta}\right)e^{ik\eta}.\label{eq:Bunch-Davies vk}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The Bunch-Davies vacuum prescription has important applications in cosmology
 where the de Sitter spacetime approximates the inflationary stage of the
 evolution of the universe.
 However, this approximation is valid only for a certain time interval,
 for instance 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}<\eta<\eta_{f}$
\end_inset 

, while at earlier times, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta<\eta_{i}$
\end_inset 

, the spacetime is not de Sitter.
 Therefore the procedure of imposing the minimum-energy conditions at earlier
 times 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta<\eta_{i}$
\end_inset 

 cannot be justified, and the BD vacuum state can be used only for modes
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\left|\eta_{i}\right|\gg1$
\end_inset 

.
 However, it is these modes that are important for cosmological predictions.
\layout Subsection

Spectrum of fluctuations in the BD vacuum
\layout Standard

Let us now compute the fluctuation amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi_{L}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 in the BD vacuum state and compare the result with the fluctuations in
 Minkowski spacetime.
\layout Standard

According to the formula\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:delta chi L}

\end_inset 

), the amplitude of fluctuations is determined by absolute values of the
 mode functions.
 Up to now we have been mostly working with the auxiliary field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}(x)=a\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $(x)$
\end_inset 

.
 The mode expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}(x)$
\end_inset 

 is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 times the mode expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, the mode functions of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}(\eta)v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{k}(\eta)$
\end_inset 

 are the mode functions of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\chi}$
\end_inset 

.
 Hence, the spectrum of fluctuations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 is 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\delta\phi_{L}(\eta)=a^{-1}(\eta)k^{3/2}\left|v_{k}(\eta)\right|=H\sqrt{k^{2}\eta^{2}+1}.\label{eq:delta phi L eta 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

This spectrum is to be compared with Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:delta chi answer}

\end_inset 

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset 

.
 The spectrum\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:delta phi L eta 1}

\end_inset 

) for early times (
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\eta\right|\gg k$
\end_inset 

) is the same as in the Minkowski spacetime, while for late times or for
 superhorizon scales (
\begin_inset Formula $k\ll\left|\eta\right|^{-1}$
\end_inset 

) the spectrum\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:delta phi L eta 1}

\end_inset 

) becomes almost independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 (
\series bold 
scale-invariant
\series default 
) and shows much larger fluctuations than the spectrum\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:delta chi answer}

\end_inset 

).
 The growth of fluctuations is due to the influence of gravity on the field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The growth of quantum fluctuations is used in cosmology to explain the formation
 of large-scale structures (galaxies and clusters of galaxies) in the early
 universe.
 The theory of 
\series bold 
cosmological inflation
\series default 
 assumes the existence of a de Sitter-like epoch in the history of the universe.
 During this epoch, vacuum fluctuations of the fields were significantly
 amplified.
 The resulting large quantum fluctuations acted as seeds for the inhomogeneities
 of energy density, which then grew by gravitational collapse and eventually
 caused the formation of galaxies.
 This theory is a practical application of quantum field theory in curved
 spacetime to astrophysics.
\layout Section

Unruh effect
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{cha:08The-Unruh-effect}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The Unruh effect predicts that particles will be detected in a vacuum by
 an accelerated observer.
 In this chapter we consider the simplest case, in which the observer moves
 with constant acceleration through Minkowski spacetime and measures the
 number of particles in a massless scalar field.
 Even though the field is in the vacuum state, the observer finds a distribution
 of particles characteristic of a thermal bath of blackbody radiation.
 
\layout Subsection

Kinematics of uniformly accelerated motion 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Kinematics-of-accelerated}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

First we consider the trajectory of an object moving with constant acceleration
 in the Minkowski spacetime.
 A model of this situation is a spaceship with an infinite energy supply
 and a propulsion engine that exerts a constant force (but moves with the
 ship).
 The resulting motion of the spaceship is such that the acceleration of
 the ship in its own frame of reference (the 
\series bold 
proper acceleration
\series default 
) is constant.
 This is the natural definition of a uniformly accelerated motion in a relativis
tic theory.
 (An object cannot move with 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mathbf{v}/dt=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset 

 for all time because its velocity is always smaller than the speed of light,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{v}\right|<1$
\end_inset 

.)
\layout Standard

We now introduce the reference frames that will play a major role in our
 considerations: the laboratory frame, the proper frame, and the comoving
 frame.
 The laboratory frame is the usual inertial reference frame with the coordinates
 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,x,y,z)$
\end_inset 

.
 The proper frame is the accelerated system of reference that moves together
 with the observer; we shall also call it the accelerated frame.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{comoving frame}

\end_inset 

The comoving frame defined at a time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is the 
\emph on 
inertial
\emph default 
 frame in which the accelerated observer is instantaneously at rest at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
 (Thus the term 
\series bold 
comoving frame
\series default 
 actually refers to a different frame for each 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset 

.)
\layout Standard

By definition, the observer's proper acceleration at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset 

-acceleration measured in the comoving frame at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
 We consider a uniformly accelerated observer whose proper acceleration
 is time-independent and equal to a given 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset 

-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset 

.
 The trajectory of such an observer may be described by a worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}(\tau)$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 is the proper time measured by the observer.
 The proper time parametrization implies the condition 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u^{\mu}u_{\mu}=1,\quad u^{\mu}\equiv\frac{dx^{\mu}}{d\tau}.\label{eq:u mu norm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

It is a standard result that the 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset 

