\layout Subsection

Coordinates in the proper frame
\layout Standard

To describe quantum fields as seen by an accelerated observer, we need to
 use the 
\series bold 
proper coordinates
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,\xi)$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 is the proper time and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset 

 is the distance measured by the observer.
 The proper coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,\xi)$
\end_inset 

 is related to the laboratory frame 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 by some transformation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 which we shall now determine.
\layout Standard

The observer's trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $t(\tau)$
\end_inset 

,\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $x(\tau)$
\end_inset 

 should correspond to the line 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=0$
\end_inset 

 in the proper coordinates.
 Let the observer hold a rigid measuring stick of proper length 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{0}$
\end_inset 

, so that the entire stick accelerates together with the observer.
 Then the stick is instantaneously at rest in the comoving frame and the
 far endpoint of the stick has the proper coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tau,\xi_{0}\right)$
\end_inset 

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

.
 We shall derive the relation between the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,\xi)$
\end_inset 

 by computing the laboratory coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 of the far end of the stick as functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

In the comoving frame at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

, the stick is represented by the 4-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{(\textrm{com})}^{\mu}\equiv\left(0,\xi_{0}\right)$
\end_inset 

 connecting the endpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,0)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tau,\xi_{0}\right)$
\end_inset 

.
 This comoving frame is an inertial system of reference moving with the
 4-velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\mu}(\tau)=dx^{\mu}/d\tau$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{(\textrm{lab})}^{\mu}$
\end_inset 

 of the stick in the laboratory frame can be found by applying the inverse
 Lorentz transformation to the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{(\textrm{com})}^{\mu}$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
s_{(\textrm{lab})}^{0}\\
s_{(\textrm{lab})}^{1}\end{array}\right]=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-v^{2}}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & v^{\,}\\
v^{\,} & 1\end{array}\right)\left[\begin{array}{c}
s_{(\textrm{com})}^{0}\\
s_{(\textrm{com})}^{1}\end{array}\right]=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
u^{0} & u^{1}\\
u^{1} & u^{0}\end{array}\right)\left[\begin{array}{c}
s_{(\textrm{com})}^{0}\\
s_{(\textrm{com})}^{1}\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
u^{1}\xi\\
u^{0}\xi\end{array}\right],\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v\equiv u^{1}/u^{0}$
\end_inset 

 is the velocity of the stick in the laboratory system.
 The stick is attached to the observer moving along 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}(\tau)$
\end_inset 

, so the proper coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,\xi)$
\end_inset 

 of the far end of the stick correspond to the laboratory coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
t(\tau,\xi) & =x^{0}(\tau)+s_{(\textrm{lab})}^{0}=x^{0}(\tau)+\frac{dx^{1}(\tau)}{d\tau}\xi,\label{eq:t tau xi}\\
x(\tau,\xi) & =x^{1}(\tau)+s_{(\textrm{lab})}^{1}=x^{1}(\tau)+\frac{dx^{0}(\tau)}{d\tau}\xi.\label{eq:x tau xi}\end{align}

\end_inset 

Note that the relations\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:t tau xi}

\end_inset 

)-(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:x tau xi}

\end_inset 

) specify the proper frame for 
\emph on 
any
\emph default 
 trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{0,1}(\tau)$
\end_inset 

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset 

+
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset 

-dimensional Minkowski spacetime.
\layout Standard

Now we can substitute Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:x t worldline}

\end_inset 

) into the above relations to compute the proper coordinates for a uniformly
 accelerated observer.
 We choose the initial conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{0}(0)=0$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}(0)=a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

 for the observer's trajectory and obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
t(\tau,\xi) & =\frac{1+a\xi}{a}\sinh a\tau,\quad x(\tau,\xi)=\frac{1+a\xi}{a}\cosh a\tau.\label{eq:t tau xi 0}\end{align}

\end_inset 

The converse relations are
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tau(t,x)=\frac{1}{2a}\ln\frac{x+t}{x-t},\quad\xi(t,x)=-a^{-1}+\sqrt{x^{2}-t^{2}}.\]

\end_inset 


\layout Subsubsection*

The horizon
\layout Standard

It can be seen from Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:t tau xi 0}

\end_inset 

) that the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,\xi)$
\end_inset 

 vary in the intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty<\tau<+\infty$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-a^{-1}<\xi<+\infty$
\end_inset 

.
 In particular, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi<-a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

 we would find 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial t/\partial\tau<0$
\end_inset 

, i.e.\SpecialChar ~
the direction of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 would be opposite to that of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

.
 One can verify that an accelerated observer cannot measure distances longer
 than 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

 in the direction opposite to the acceleration, for instance, the distances
 to the events 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

 in Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:wl1}

\end_inset 

.
 A measurement of the distance to a point requires to place a clock at that
 point and to synchronize that clock with the observer's clock.
 However, the observer cannot synchronize clocks with the events 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

 because no signals can be ever received from these events.
 One says that the accelerated observer perceives a 
\series bold 
horizon
\series default 
 at proper distance 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The existence of the horizon can be easily seen by the following qualitative
 considerations.
 The accelerated observer measures a constant gravitational field with accelerat
ion 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

 pointing in the negative 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 direction.
 Consider a photon of energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset 

 propagating 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

upwards
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 in the gravitational field.
 After ascending to a height 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta h$
\end_inset 

, the photon loses energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E=-Ea\Delta h$
\end_inset 

.
 After ascending to the height 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta h=a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

, the photon would lose all its kinetic energy and will not be able to continue
 moving upwards.
 (This calculation is of course not rigorous but does give the correct answer.)
\layout Standard

The coordinate system\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:t tau xi 0}

\end_inset 

) is 
\emph on 
incomplete
\emph default 
 and covers only a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

quarter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 of the Minkowski spacetime, consisting of the subdomain 
\begin_inset Formula $x>\left|t\right|$
\end_inset 

 (see Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:wl2}

\end_inset 

).
 This is the subdomain of the Minkowski spacetime accessible to a uniformly
 accelerated observer.
 For instance, the events 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset 

 cannot be described by (real) values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset 

.
 The past lightcone 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-t$
\end_inset 

 corresponds to the proper coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=-\infty$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=-a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

.
 The observer can see signals from the event 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset 

, however these signals appear to have originated not from 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset 

 but from the horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=-a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

 in the infinite past 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=-\infty$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Another way to see that the line 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=-a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

 is a horizon is to consider a line of constant proper length 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=\xi_{0}>-a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

.
 It follows from Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:t tau xi 0}

\end_inset 

) that the line 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=\xi_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is a trajectory of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-t^{2}=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset 

 with the proper acceleration 
\begin_inset Formula \[
a_{0}\equiv\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^{2}-t^{2}}}=\left(\xi_{0}+a^{-1}\right)^{-1}.\]

\end_inset 

 Therefore, the worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=-a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

 would have to represent an infinite proper acceleration, which would require
 an infinitely large force and is thus impossible.
 It follows that an accelerated observer cannot hold a rigid measuring stick
 longer than 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

 in the direction opposite to acceleration.
 (A 
\series bold 
rigid
\series default 
 stick is one that would keep its proper distance constant in the observer's
 reference frame.)
\layout Standard


