\layout Subsection

Rindler spacetime
\layout Standard

It is straightforward to show that the Minkowski metric in the proper coordinate
s 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,\xi)$
\end_inset 

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ds^{2}=dt^{2}-dx^{2}=(1+a\xi)^{2}d\tau^{2}-d\xi^{2}.\label{eq:Rindler metric 0}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The spacetime with this metric is called the Rindler spacetime.
 The curvature of the Rindler spacetime is everywhere zero since it differs
 from the Minkowski spacetime merely by a change of coordinates.
 
\layout Standard

To develop the quantum field theory in the Rindler spacetime, we first rewrite
 the metric\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Rindler metric 0}

\end_inset 

) in a conformally flat form.
 This can be achieved by choosing the new spatial coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\xi}$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\xi=(1+a\xi)d\tilde{\xi}$
\end_inset 

, because in that case both 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tau^{2}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tilde{\xi}^{2}$
\end_inset 

 will have a common factor 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+a\xi)^{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 (Note that the new coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\xi}$
\end_inset 

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

conformal distance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 fully analogous to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

conformal time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset 

 used in Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Quantization-of-scalar1}

\end_inset 

.) The necessary replacement is therefore
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\xi}\equiv\frac{1}{a}\ln(1+a\xi).\]

\end_inset 

 Since the proper distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset 

 is constrained by 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi>-a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

, the conformal distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\xi}$
\end_inset 

 varies in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty<\tilde{\xi}<+\infty$
\end_inset 

.
 The metric becomes
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ds^{2}=e^{2a\tilde{\xi}}(d\tau^{2}-d\tilde{\xi}^{2}).\label{eq:Rindler metric conf}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The relation between the laboratory coordinates and the conformal coordinates
 is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
t(\tau,\tilde{\xi})=a^{-1}e^{a\tilde{\xi}}\sinh a\tau,\quad x(\tau,\tilde{\xi})=a^{-1}e^{a\tilde{\xi}}\cosh a\tau.\label{eq:t tau xi conf}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Subsection

Quantum field in Rindler spacetime
\layout Standard

The goal of this section is to quantize a scalar field in the proper reference
 frame of a uniformly accelerated observer.
 To simplify the problem, we consider a massless scalar field in the 1+1-dimensi
onal spacetime.
 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Conformally-coupled-field}

\end_inset 

The action for a massless scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[\phi]=\frac{1}{2}\int g^{\alpha\beta}\phi_{,\alpha}\phi_{,\beta}\sqrt{-g}d^{2}x.\]

\end_inset 

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}\equiv(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 is the two-dimensional coordinate.
 It is easy to see that this action is conformally invariant: indeed, if
 we replace 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\alpha\beta}\rightarrow\tilde{g}_{\alpha\beta}=\Omega^{2}(t,x)g_{\alpha\beta},\]

\end_inset 

then the determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset 

 and the contravariant metric are replaced by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sqrt{-g}\rightarrow\Omega^{2}\sqrt{-g},\quad g^{\alpha\beta}\rightarrow\Omega^{-2}g^{\alpha\beta},\label{eq:2d conf inv field}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

so the factors 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{2}$
\end_inset 

 cancel in the action.
 The conformal invariance causes a significant simplification of the theory
 in 1+1 dimensions (a calculation for massive field in 3+1 dimensions would
 be more complicated).
 
\layout Standard

In the laboratory coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,x)$
\end_inset 

, the action is
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[\phi]=\frac{1}{2}\int\left[\left(\partial_{t}\phi\right)^{2}-\left(\partial_{x}\phi\right)^{2}\right]dt\, dx.\]

\end_inset 

In the conformal coordinates, the metric\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Rindler metric conf}

\end_inset 

) is equal to the flat Minkowski metric multiplied by a conformal factor
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{2}(\tau,\tilde{\xi})\equiv\exp(2a\tilde{\xi})$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, due to the conformal invariance, the action has the same form
 in the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,\tilde{\xi})$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
S[\phi]=\frac{1}{2}\int\left[\left(\partial_{\tau}\phi\right)^{2}-(\partial_{\tilde{\xi}}\phi)^{2}\right]d\tau\, d\tilde{\xi}.\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The classical equations of motion in the laboratory frame and in the accelerated
 frame are
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial^{2}\phi}{\partial t^{2}}-\frac{\partial^{2}\phi}{\partial x^{2}}=0;\quad\frac{\partial^{2}\phi}{\partial\tau^{2}}-\frac{\partial^{2}\phi}{\partial\tilde{\xi}^{2}}=0,\]

\end_inset 

with the general solutions 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi(t,x)=A(t-x)+B(t+x),\quad\phi(\tau,\tilde{\xi})=P(\tau-\tilde{\xi})+Q(\tau+\tilde{\xi}).\]

\end_inset 

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

 are arbitrary smooth functions.
 Note that a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 representing a certain state of the field will be a very different function
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\xi}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Quantization-Rindler}

\end_inset 

We shall now quantize the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

 and compare the vacuum states in the laboratory frame and in the accelerated
 frame.
 
\layout Standard

The procedure of quantization is formally the same in both coordinate systems
 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,x)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,\tilde{\xi})$
\end_inset 

.
 The mode expansion in the laboratory frame is found from Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi decomp}

\end_inset 

) with the substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}=\left|k\right|$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\phi}(t,x)=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{dk}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\left|k\right|}}\left[e^{-i\left|k\right|t+ikx}\hat{a}_{k}^{-}+e^{i\left|k\right|t-ikx}\hat{a}_{k}^{+}\right].\label{eq:1+1d mode exp}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The normalization factor 
\begin_inset Formula $(2\pi)^{1/2}$
\end_inset 

 is used in 1+1 dimensions instead of the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $(2\pi)^{3/2}$
\end_inset 

 used in 3+1 dimensions.
 The creation and annihilation operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{k}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 defined by Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:1+1d mode exp}

\end_inset 

) satisfy the usual commutation relations and describe particles moving
 with momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 either in the positive 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 direction (
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset 

) or in the negative 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 direction (
\begin_inset Formula $k<0$
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

The vacuum state in the laboratory frame (the 
\series bold 
Minkowski vacuum
\series default 
), denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, is the zero eigenvector of all the annihilation operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{k}^{-}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{a}_{k}^{-}\left|0_{M}\right\rangle =0\;\:\textrm{for all }k.\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The mode expansion in the accelerated frame is quite similar to Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:1+1d mode exp}

\end_inset 

),
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\phi}(\tau,\tilde{\xi})=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{dk}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\left|k\right|}}\left[e^{-i\left|k\right|\tau+ik\tilde{\xi}}\hat{b}_{k}^{-}+e^{i\left|k\right|\tau-ik\tilde{\xi}}\hat{b}_{k}^{+}\right].\label{eq:1+1d mode Ri}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Note that the mode expansions\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:1+1d mode exp}

\end_inset 

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:1+1d mode Ri}

\end_inset 

) are decompositions of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}(x,t)$
\end_inset 

 into linear combinations of two different sets of basis functions with
 operator-valued coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{k}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{k}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

.
 So it is to be expected that the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{k}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{k}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 are different, although they satisfy similar commutation relations.
\layout Standard

The vacuum state in the accelerated frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 (the 
\series bold 
Rindler vacuum
\series default 
) is defined by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{b}_{k}^{-}\left|0_{R}\right\rangle =0\;\:\textrm{for all }k.\]

\end_inset 

 Since the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{k}$
\end_inset 

 differ from 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{k}$
\end_inset 

, the Rindler vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and the Minkowski vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 are two different quantum states of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

At this point, a natural question to ask is whether the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

correct
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 vacuum.
 To answer this question, we need to consider the physical interpretation
 of the states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 in a particular (perhaps imaginary) physical experiment.
 Let us imagine a hypothetical device for preparing the quantum field in
 the lowest-energy state; this device may work by pumping all energy, as
 much as possible, out of a certain volume.
 If mounted onto an accelerated spaceship, the device will prepare the field
 in the quantum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 Observers moving with the ship would agree that the field in the state
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 has the lowest possible energy and the Minkowski state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 has a higher energy.
 Thus a particle detector at rest in the accelerated frame 
\emph on 
will register particles
\emph default 
 when the scalar field is in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Neither of the two vacuum states is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

more correct
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 if considered by itself, without regard for realistic physical conditions
 in the universe.
 Ultimately the choice of vacuum is determined by experiment: the correct
 vacuum state must be such that the theoretical predictions agree with the
 available experimental data.
 For instance, the spacetime near the Solar system is approximately flat
 (almost Minkowski), and we observe empty space that does not create any
 particles by itself.
 By virtue of this observation, we are justified to ascribe the vacuum state
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 to fields in the empty Minkowski spacetime.
 In particular, an accelerated observer moving through empty space will
 encounter fields in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and therefore will detect particles.
 This detection is a manifestation of the Unruh effect.
\layout Standard

The rest of this chapter is devoted to a calculation relating the Minkowski
 frame operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{k}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 to the Rindler frame operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{k}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 through the appropriate Bogolyubov coefficients.
 This calculation will enable us to express the Minkowski vacuum as a superposit
ion of excited states built on top of the Rindler vacuum and thus to compute
 the probability distribution for particle occupation numbers observed in
 the accelerated frame.
\layout Subsection

Lightcone mode expansions 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Lightcone-mode-expansions}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

It is convenient to introduce the lightcone coordinates
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed false

\layout Standard

The chosen notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(u,v\right)$
\end_inset 

 for the lightcone coordinates in a uniformly accelerated frame and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right)$
\end_inset 

 for the freely falling (unaccelerated) frame will be used in chapter\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cha:09The-Hawking-effect}

\end_inset 

 as well.
 
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \[
\bar{u}\equiv t-x,\:\bar{v}\equiv t+x;\quad u\equiv\tau-\tilde{\xi},\: v\equiv\tau+\tilde{\xi}.\]

\end_inset 

The relation between the laboratory frame and the accelerated frame has
 a simpler form in lightcone coordinates: from Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:t tau xi conf}

\end_inset 

) we find
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\bar{u}=-a^{-1}e^{-au},\quad\bar{v}=a^{-1}e^{av},\label{eq:ubar vbar u v}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

so the metric is
\begin_inset Formula \[
ds^{2}=d\bar{u}\, d\bar{v}=e^{a(v-u)}du\, dv.\]

\end_inset 

The field equations and their general solutions are also expressed more
 concisely in the lightcone coordinates:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial\bar{u}\partial\bar{v}}\phi\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right)=0,\quad\phi\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right)=A\left(\bar{u}\right)+B\left(\bar{v}\right);\nonumber \\
\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial u\partial v}\phi(u,v)=0,\quad\phi(u,v)=P(u)+Q(v).\label{eq:phi gen sol u v}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The mode expansion\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:1+1d mode exp}

\end_inset 

) can be rewritten in the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u},\bar{v}$
\end_inset 

 by first splitting the integration into the ranges of positive and negative
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\hat{\phi}(t,x)= & \int_{-\infty}^{0}\frac{dk}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\left|k\right|}}\left[e^{ikt+ikx}\hat{a}_{k}^{-}+e^{-ikt-ikx}\hat{a}_{k}^{+}\right]\\
 & +\int_{0}^{+\infty}\frac{dk}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2k}}\left[e^{-ikt+ikx}\hat{a}_{k}^{-}+e^{ikt-ikx}\hat{a}_{k}^{+}\right].\end{align*}

\end_inset 

Then we introduce 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\left|k\right|$
\end_inset 

 as the integration variable with the range 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\omega<+\infty$
\end_inset 

 and obtain the 
\series bold 
lightcone mode expansion
\series default 

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\phi}\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right)=\int_{0}^{+\infty}\frac{d\omega}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega}}\left[e^{-i\omega\bar{u}}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-}+e^{i\omega\bar{u}}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{+}+e^{-i\omega\bar{v}}\hat{a}_{-\omega}^{-}+e^{i\omega\bar{v}}\hat{a}_{-\omega}^{+}\right].\label{eq:phi lc exp lab}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Lightcone mode expansions explicitly decompose the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right)$
\end_inset 

 into a sum of functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}$
\end_inset 

 and functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{v}$
\end_inset 

.
 This agrees with Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi gen sol u v}

\end_inset 

) from which we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\bar{u})$
\end_inset 

 is a linear combination of the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 with positive momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset 

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\bar{v})$
\end_inset 

 is a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{-\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 with negative momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $-\omega$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\hat{\phi}\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right) & =\hat{A}\left(\bar{u}\right)+\hat{B}\left(\bar{v}\right);\\
\hat{A}\left(\bar{u}\right) & =\int_{0}^{+\infty}\frac{d\omega}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega}}\left[e^{-i\omega\bar{u}}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-}+e^{i\omega\bar{u}}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{+}\right],\\
\hat{B}\left(\bar{v}\right) & =\int_{0}^{+\infty}\frac{d\omega}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega}}\left[e^{-i\omega\bar{v}}\hat{a}_{-\omega}^{-}+e^{i\omega\bar{v}}\hat{a}_{-\omega}^{+}\right].\end{align*}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The lightcone mode expansion in the Rindler frame has exactly the same form
 except for involving the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)$
\end_inset 

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bar{u},\bar{v})$
\end_inset 

.
 We use the integration variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset 

 to distinguish the Rindler frame expansion from that of the Minkowski frame,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\hat{\phi}(u,v) & =\hat{P}(u)+\hat{Q}(v)\nonumber \\
 & =\int_{0}^{+\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\Omega}}\left[e^{-i\Omega u}\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-}+e^{i\Omega u}\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{+}+e^{-i\Omega v}\hat{b}_{-\Omega}^{-}+e^{i\Omega v}\hat{b}_{-\Omega}^{+}\right].\label{eq:phi lc exp Ri}\end{align}

\end_inset 

 As before, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}(u)$
\end_inset 

 is expanded into operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 with positive momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}(v)$
\end_inset 

 into the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{-\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 with negative momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $-\Omega$
\end_inset 

.
 (Note that the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset 

 take only 
\emph on 
positive
\emph default 
 values.
 Also, the Rindler mode expansion is only valid within the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $x>\left|t\right|$
\end_inset 

 covered by the Rindler frame; it is only within this domain that we can
 compare the two mode expansions.)
\layout Subsection

Bogolyubov transformations
\layout Standard

The relation between the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\pm\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\pm\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

, which we shall presently derive, is a Bogolyubov transformation of a more
 general form than that considered in Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Bogolyubov-transformations}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Since the coordinate transformation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ubar vbar u v}

\end_inset 

) does not mix 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset 

, the identity
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\phi}(u,v)=\hat{A}\left(\bar{u}(u)\right)+\hat{B}\left(\bar{v}(v)\right)=\hat{P}(u)+\hat{Q}(v)\]

\end_inset 

entails two separate relations for 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset 

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{A}\left(\bar{u}(u)\right)=\hat{P}(u),\quad\hat{B}\left(\bar{v}(v)\right)=\hat{Q}(v).\]

\end_inset 

Comparing the expansions\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi lc exp lab}

\end_inset 

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi lc exp Ri}

\end_inset 

), we find that the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 with positive momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset 

 are expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 with positive momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset 

, while the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{-\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 are expressed through negative-momentum operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{-\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

.
 In other words, there is no mixing between operators of positive and negative
 momentum.
 The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\left(\bar{u}\right)=\hat{P}(u)$
\end_inset 

 is then rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\hat{A}\left(\bar{u}\right) & =\int_{0}^{+\infty}\frac{d\omega}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega}}\left[e^{-i\omega\bar{u}}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-}+e^{i\omega\bar{u}}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{+}\right]\nonumber \\
=\hat{P}(u) & =\int_{0}^{+\infty}\frac{d\Omega}{(2\pi)^{1/2}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\Omega}}\left[e^{-i\Omega u}\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-}+e^{i\Omega u}\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{+}\right].\label{eq:a b M Ri}\end{align}

\end_inset 

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}$
\end_inset 

 is understood to be the function of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset 

 given by Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ubar vbar u v}

\end_inset 

); both sides of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:a b M Ri}

\end_inset 

) are equal as functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

We can now express the positive-momentum operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 as explicit linear combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

.
 To this end, we perform the Fourier transform of both sides of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:a b M Ri}

\end_inset 

) in 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset 

.
 The RHS yields
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{du}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{i\Omega u}\hat{P}(u)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\left|\Omega\right|}}\left\{ \begin{array}{l}
\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-},\quad\Omega>0;\\
\hat{b}_{\left|\Omega\right|}^{+},\;\,\Omega<0.\end{array}\right.\label{eq:P rhs}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

(The Fourier transform variable is denoted also by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset 

 for convenience.) The Fourier transform of the LHS of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:a b M Ri}

\end_inset 

) yields an expression involving all 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{du}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{i\Omega u}\hat{A}\left(\bar{u}\right) & =\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega}{\sqrt{2\omega}}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{du}{2\pi}\left[e^{i\Omega u-i\omega\bar{u}}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-}+e^{i\Omega u+i\omega\bar{u}}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{+}\right]\nonumber \\
 & \equiv\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{d\omega}{\sqrt{2\omega}}\left[F(\omega,\Omega)\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-}+F(-\omega,\Omega)\hat{a}_{\omega}^{+}\right],\label{eq:A lhs}\end{align}

\end_inset 

where we introduced the auxiliary function
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed true

\layout Standard

Because of the carelessly interchanged order of integration while deriving
 Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:A lhs}

\end_inset 

), the integral (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:F def}

\end_inset 

) diverges at 
\begin_inset Formula $u\rightarrow+\infty$
\end_inset 

, so the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\omega,\Omega)$
\end_inset 

 must be given more carefully if we desire full mathematical rigor.
 
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F(\omega,\Omega)\equiv\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{du}{2\pi}e^{i\Omega u-i\omega\bar{u}}=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{du}{2\pi}\exp\left[i\Omega u+i\frac{\omega}{a}e^{-au}\right].\label{eq:F def}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Comparing Eqs.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:P rhs}

\end_inset 

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:A lhs}

\end_inset 

) restricted to positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset 

, we find that the relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-}$
\end_inset 

 is of the form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-}=\int_{0}^{\infty}d\omega\left[\alpha_{\omega\Omega}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-}+\beta_{\omega\Omega}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{+}\right],\label{eq:Bogo omega}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\omega\Omega}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{\omega\Omega}$
\end_inset 

 are
\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{Bogolyubov transformation!general form}

\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\alpha_{\omega\Omega}=\sqrt{\frac{\Omega}{\omega}}F(\omega,\Omega),\quad\beta_{\omega\Omega}=\sqrt{\frac{\Omega}{\omega}}F(-\omega,\Omega);\quad\omega>0,\Omega>0.\label{eq:Bogo coeffs omega}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{+}$
\end_inset 

 can be similarly expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 using the Hermitian conjugation of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bogo omega}

\end_inset 

) and the identity 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F^{*}(\omega,\Omega)=F(-\omega,-\Omega).\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The relation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bogo omega}

\end_inset 

) is a Bogolyubov transformation that mixes creation and annihilation operators
 with different momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\neq\Omega$
\end_inset 

.
 In contrast, the Bogolyubov transformations considered in Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Bogolyubov-transformations}

\end_inset 

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

diagonal,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\omega\Omega}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{\omega\Omega}$
\end_inset 

 proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(\omega-\Omega)$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The relation between the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{-\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{-\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 is obtained from the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}\left(\bar{v}\right)=\hat{Q}(v)$
\end_inset 

.
 We omit the corresponding straightforward calculations and concentrate
 on the modes with positive momentum; the results for negative momenta are
 completely analogous.
\layout Subsubsection*

General Bogolyubov transformations
\layout Standard

We now briefly consider the properties of a general Bogolyubov transformation,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-}=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}d\omega\left[\alpha_{\omega\Omega}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-}+\beta_{\omega\Omega}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{+}\right].\label{eq:Bogo trans gen}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The relation\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bogo omega}

\end_inset 

) is of this form except for the integration over 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\omega<+\infty$
\end_inset 

 which is justified because the only nonzero Bogolyubov coefficients are
 those relating the momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega,\Omega$
\end_inset 

 of equal sign, i.e.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{-\omega,\Omega}=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{-\omega,\Omega}=0$
\end_inset 

.
 But for now we shall not limit ourselves to this case.
\layout Standard

The relation for the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{+}$
\end_inset 

 is the Hermitian conjugate of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bogo trans gen}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard
\noindent 

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
startremark
\end_inset 


\series bold 
 Remark: 
\series default 
 To avoid confusion in the notation, we always write the indices 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega,\Omega$
\end_inset 

 in the Bogolyubov coefficients in this order, i.e.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\omega\Omega}$
\end_inset 

, but never 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\Omega\omega}$
\end_inset 

.
 In the calculations throughout this chapter, the integration is always
 over the first index 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset 

 corresponding to the momentum of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

-particles.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
eofremark
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Since the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

,\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 satisfy the commutation relations
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-},\hat{a}_{\omega'}^{+}\right]=\delta(\omega-\omega'),\quad[\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-},\hat{b}_{\Omega'}^{+}]=\delta(\Omega-\Omega'),\label{eq:a b omega comm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

it is straightforward to check (by substituting Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bogo trans gen}

\end_inset 

) into the above relation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

) that the Bogolyubov coefficients are constrained by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}d\omega\left(\alpha_{\omega\Omega}\alpha_{\omega\Omega'}^{*}-\beta_{\omega\Omega}\beta_{\omega\Omega'}^{*}\right)=\delta(\Omega-\Omega').\label{eq:alpha beta omega norm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 This is analogous to the normalization condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\alpha_{k}\right|^{2}-\left|\beta_{k}\right|^{2}=1$
\end_inset 

 we had earlier.
\layout Standard

Note that the origin of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset 

 function in Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:a b omega comm}

\end_inset 

) is the infinite volume of the entire space.
 If the field were quantized in a finite box of volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset 

, the momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset 

 would be discrete and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset 

 function would be replaced by the ordinary Kronecker symbol times the volume
 factor, i.e.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\Omega\Omega'}V$
\end_inset 

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset 

 function in Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:alpha beta omega norm}

\end_inset 

) has the same origin.
 Below we shall use Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:alpha beta omega norm}

\end_inset 

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\Omega'$
\end_inset 

 and the divergent factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(0)$
\end_inset 

 will be interpreted as the infinite spatial volume.
 
\layout Subsection

Density of particles
\layout Standard

Since the vacua 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 corresponding to the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-}$
\end_inset 

 are different, the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

-vacuum is a state with 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particles and vice versa.
 We now compute the density of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particles in the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

-vacuum state.
\layout Standard

The 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particle number operator is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}_{\Omega}\equiv\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{+}\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-}$
\end_inset 

, so the average 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

-particle number in the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

-vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is equal to the expectation value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}_{\Omega}$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\langle\hat{N}_{\Omega}\rangle & \equiv\left\langle 0_{M}\right|\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{+}\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-}\left|0_{M}\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & =\left\langle 0_{M}\right|\int\! d\omega\left[\alpha_{\omega\Omega}^{*}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{+}+\beta_{\omega\Omega}^{*}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-}\right]\int\! d\omega'\left[\alpha_{\omega'\Omega}\hat{a}_{\omega'}^{-}+\beta_{\omega'\Omega}\hat{a}_{\omega'}^{+}\right]\left|0_{M}\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & =\int\! d\omega\left|\beta_{\omega\Omega}\right|^{2}.\label{eq:N Omega density}\end{align}

\end_inset 

This is the mean number of particles observed in the accelerated frame.
 
\layout Standard

In principle one can explicitly compute the Bogolyubov coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{\omega\Omega}$
\end_inset 

 defined by Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Bogo coeffs omega}

\end_inset 

) in terms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset 

 function (see below).
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:The-Unruh-temperature}

\end_inset 

However, we only need to evaluate the RHS of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:N Omega density}

\end_inset 

) which involves an integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset 

, and we shall use a mathematical trick that allows us to compute just that
 integral and avoid other, more cumbersome calculations.
 
\layout Standard

We first show that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\omega,\Omega)$
\end_inset 

 satisfies the identity 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F(\omega,\Omega)=F(-\omega,\Omega)\exp\left(\frac{\pi\Omega}{a}\right),\quad\textrm{for }\omega>0,\: a>0.\label{eq:F relation}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard
\noindent 

