\end_inset 


\series bold 
 Derivation of Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:F relation}

\end_inset 

)
\layout Standard

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\omega,\Omega)$
\end_inset 

 can be reduced to Euler's 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset 

 function by changing the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $u\rightarrow t$
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
t\equiv-\frac{i\omega}{a}e^{-au}.\]

\end_inset 

The result is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F(\omega,\Omega)=\frac{1}{2\pi a}\exp\left(i\frac{\Omega}{a}\ln\frac{\omega}{a}+\frac{\pi\Omega}{2a}\right)\Gamma\left(-\frac{i\Omega}{a}\right),\quad\omega>0,\, a>0.\]

\end_inset 

 However, it is not clear whether to take 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(-\omega)=\ln\omega+i\pi$
\end_inset 

 or some other phase instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $i\pi$
\end_inset 

 in the above expression.
 To resolve this question, we need to analyze the required analytic continuation
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset 

 function more carefully.
\layout Standard

A direct approach (without using the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset 

 function) is to deform the contour of integration in Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:F def}

\end_inset 

).
 The contour can be shifted downwards by 
\begin_inset Formula $-i\pi a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

 into the line 
\begin_inset Formula $u=-i\pi a^{-1}+t$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 is real, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty<t<+\infty$
\end_inset 

 (see Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:cont3}

\end_inset 

).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-au}=-e^{-at}$
\end_inset 

 and we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \[
F(\omega,\Omega)=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{dt}{2\pi}\exp\left(i\Omega t+\frac{\pi\Omega}{a}-\frac{i\omega}{a}e^{-at}\right)=F(-\omega,\Omega)\exp\left(\frac{\pi\Omega}{a}\right).\]

\end_inset 

It remains to justify the shift of the contour.
 The integrand has no singularities and, since the lateral lines have a
 limited length, it is enough to show that the integrand vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $u\rightarrow\pm\infty-i\alpha$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\alpha<\pi a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $u=M-i\alpha$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset 

 the integrand vanishes since 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{u\rightarrow-\infty-i\alpha}Re\left(\frac{i\omega}{a}e^{-au}\right)=-\lim_{t\rightarrow-\infty}\frac{\omega}{a}e^{-at}\sin\alpha a=-\infty.\label{eq:alpha limit}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

At 
\begin_inset Formula $u\rightarrow+\infty-i\alpha$
\end_inset 

 the integral does not actually converge and must be regularized, e.g.\SpecialChar ~
by inserting
 a convergence factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(-bu^{2}\right)$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F(\omega,\Omega)=\lim_{b\rightarrow+0}\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\frac{du}{2\pi}\exp\left(-bu^{2}+i\Omega u+i\frac{\omega}{a}e^{-au}\right).\label{eq:F reg}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 With this (or another) regularization, the integrand vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $u\rightarrow+\infty-i\alpha$
\end_inset 

 as well.
 Therefore the contour may be shifted and our result is justified in the
 regularized sense.
\layout Standard

Note that we cannot shift the contour to 
\begin_inset Formula $u=-i(\pi+2\pi n)a^{-1}+t$
\end_inset 

 with any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\neq0$
\end_inset 

 because Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:alpha limit}

\end_inset 

) will not hold.
 Also, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega<0$
\end_inset 

 we will be unable to move the contour in the negative imaginary direction.
 The shift of the contour we used is the only one possible.
