\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
n_{\Omega}=\left[\exp\left(\frac{2\pi\Omega}{a}\right)-1\right]^{-1}.\label{eq:n Omega ans}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

This is the main result of this chapter.
\layout Standard

So far we have computed 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\Omega}$
\end_inset 

 only for positive-momentum modes (with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega>0$
\end_inset 

).
 The result for negative-momentum modes is obtained by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset 

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Omega\right|$
\end_inset 

 in Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:n Omega ans}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Subsection

Unruh temperature 
\layout Standard

A massless particle with momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset 

 has energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\left|\Omega\right|$
\end_inset 

, so the formula (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:n Omega ans}

\end_inset 

) is equivalent to the Bose-Einstein distribution
\begin_inset Formula \[
n(E)=\left[\exp\left(\frac{E}{T}\right)-1\right]^{-1}\]

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset 

 is the 
\series bold 
Unruh temperature
\series default 

\begin_inset Formula \[
T\equiv\frac{a}{2\pi}.\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

We found that an accelerated observer detects particles when the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 is in the Minkowski vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 The detected particles may have any momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset 

, although the probability for registering a high-energy particle is very
 small.
 The particle distribution\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:n Omega ans}

\end_inset 

) is characteristic of the thermal blackbody radiation with the temperature
 
\begin_inset Formula $T=a/2\pi$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

 is the magnitude of the proper acceleration (in Planck units).
 An accelerated detector behaves as though it were placed in a thermal bath
 with temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset 

.
 This is the Unruh effect.
 
\layout Standard

A physical interpretation of the Unruh effect as seen in the laboratory
 frame is the following.
 The accelerated detector is coupled to the quantum fields and perturbs
 their quantum state around its trajectory.
 This perturbation is very small but as a result the detector registers
 particles, although the fields were previously in the vacuum state.
 The detected particles are real and the energy for these particles comes
 from the agent that accelerates the detector.
 
\layout Standard

Finally, we note that the Unruh effect is impossible to use in practice
 because the acceleration required to produce a measurable temperature is
 enormous.
 Here is an example calculation.
 Let us determine the acceleration corresponding to the Unruh temperature
 
\begin_inset Formula $T=100^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

C; in that case, water will boil in an accelerated container due to the
 Unruh effect.
 We need to express all quantities in the SI units.
 The equation 
\begin_inset Formula $T=a/(2\pi)$
\end_inset 

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
kT=\frac{\hbar}{c}\frac{a}{2\pi}.\]

\end_inset 

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $k\approx1.38\cdot10^{-23}$
\end_inset 

J/K is Boltzmann's constant.
 The boiling point of water is 
\begin_inset Formula $T=373$
\end_inset 

K.
 The required acceleration is 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim10^{22}$
\end_inset 

m/s
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset 

 which is clearly beyond any practical possibility.
 The Unruh effect is an extremely inefficient way to produce particles.
 
\layout Section

Hawking radiation
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{cha:09The-Hawking-effect}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Classical general relativity describes black holes as massive objects with
 such a strong gravitational field that even light cannot escape their surface
 (the 
\series bold 
black hole
\series default 
 
\series bold 
horizon
\series default 
).
 However, quantum theory predicts that black holes emit particles moving
 away from the horizon.
 The particles are produced out of vacuum fluctuations of quantum fields
 present around the black hole.
 In effect, a black hole (BH) is not completely black but radiates a dim
 light as if it were an object with a low but nonzero temperature.
 
\layout Standard

The main focus of this chapter is to compute the density of particles emitted
 by a static black hole, as registered by observers far away from the BH
 horizon.
\layout Subsection

Scalar field in Schwarzschild spacetime
\layout Standard

We consider a scalar field in the presence of a single nonrotating black
 hole of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset 

.
 The BH spacetime is described by the 
\series bold 
Schwarzschild metric
\series default 
,
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed false

\layout Standard

In our notation here and below, the asimuthal angle is 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset 

 while the scalar field is 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

.
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
ds^{2}=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)dt^{2}-\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{-1}dr^{2}-r^{2}\left(d\theta^{2}+d\varphi^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\right).\]

\end_inset 

This metric is singular at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2M$
\end_inset 

 which corresponds to the BH horizon, while for 
\begin_inset Formula $r<2M$
\end_inset 

 the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 is spacelike and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 is timelike.
 Therefore the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,r)$
\end_inset 

 may be used with the normal interpretation of time and space only in the
 exterior region, 
\begin_inset Formula $r>2M$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

To simplify the calculations, we assume that the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

 is independent of the angular variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta,\varphi$
\end_inset 

 and restrict our attention to a 1+1-dimensional section of the spacetime
 with the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,r)$
\end_inset 

.
 The line element in 1+1 dimensions, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
ds^{2}=g_{ab}dx^{a}dx^{b},\quad x^{0}\equiv t,\: x^{1}\equiv r,\]

\end_inset 

involves the reduced metric
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{ab}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1-\frac{2M}{r} & 0\\
0 & -\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{-1}\end{array}\right].\]

\end_inset 

The theory we are developing is a toy model (i.e.\SpecialChar ~
a drastically simplified
 version) of the full 3+1-dimensional theory in the Schwarzschild spacetime.
 We expect that the main features of the full theory are preserved in the
 1+1-dimensional model.
\layout Standard

The action for a massless scalar field is
\begin_inset Formula \[
S\left[\phi\right]=\frac{1}{2}\int g^{ab}\phi_{,a}\phi_{,b}\sqrt{-g}d^{2}x.\]

\end_inset 

 As shown before, this action is in fact conformally invariant.
 Because of the conformal invariance, a significant simplification occurs
 if the metric is brought to a conformally flat form.
 This is achieved by a change of coordinates similar to that employed in
 previous section.
 Namely, we introduce a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

conformal distance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}$
\end_inset 

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}=f(r)$
\end_inset 

 and the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(r)$
\end_inset 

 is chosen such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
ds^{2}=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)dt^{2}-\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{-1}dr^{2}=A(r)\left[dt^{2}-dr^{*2}\right],\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A(r)$
\end_inset 

 is some function.
 It follows that we must choose
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{df(r)}{dr}=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)^{-1};\quad dr=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)dr^{*}.\]

\end_inset 

From this relation we find 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}(r)$
\end_inset 

 up to an integration constant which we choose as 
\begin_inset Formula $2M$
\end_inset 

 for convenience,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
r^{*}(r)=r-2M+2M\ln\left(\frac{r}{2M}-1\right).\label{eq:r tortoise def 1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The metric in the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,r^{*}\right)$
\end_inset 

 is conformally flat,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ds^{2}=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)\left[dt^{2}-dr^{*2}\right],\label{eq:t rstar metric}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 must be expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}$
\end_inset 

 using Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:r tortoise def 1}

\end_inset 

).
 However, we shall not need an explicit formula for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $r(r^{*})$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}(r)$
\end_inset 

 is defined only for 
\begin_inset Formula $r>2M$
\end_inset 

 and varies in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty<r^{*}<+\infty$
\end_inset 

.
 It is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

tortoise coordinate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 because an object approaching the horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2M$
\end_inset 

 needs to cross an infinite coordinate distance in 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}$
\end_inset 

.
 From Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:t rstar metric}

\end_inset 

) it is clear that the tortoise coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,r^{*}\right)$
\end_inset 

 are asymptotically the same as the Minkowski coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,r)$
\end_inset 

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow+\infty$
\end_inset 

, i.e.\SpecialChar ~
in regions far from the black hole where the spacetime is almost flat.
\layout Standard

The action for the scalar field in the tortoise coordinates is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
S\left[\phi\right]=\frac{1}{2}\int\left[\left(\partial_{t}\phi\right)^{2}-\left(\partial_{r^{*}}\phi\right)^{2}\right]dt\, dr^{*},\]

\end_inset 

and the general solution of the equation of motion is of the form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi\left(t,r^{*}\right)=P\left(t-r^{*}\right)+Q\left(t+r^{*}\right),\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

 are arbitrary (but sufficiently smooth) functions.
 
\layout Standard

In the lightcone coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)$
\end_inset 

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u\equiv t-r^{*},\quad v\equiv t+r^{*},\label{eq:u v t rstar def}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

the metric is expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ds^{2}=\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)du\, dv.\label{eq:du dv metric}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2M$
\end_inset 

 is a singularity where the metric becomes degenerate.
\layout Subsection

Kruskal coordinates
\layout Standard

The coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,r^{*}\right)$
\end_inset 

 has the advantage that for 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}\rightarrow+\infty$
\end_inset 

 it asymptotically coincides with the Minkowski coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,r)$
\end_inset 

 naturally defined far away from the BH horizon.
 However, the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,r^{*}\right)$
\end_inset 

 do not cover the black hole interior, 
\begin_inset Formula $r<2M$
\end_inset 

.
 To describe the entire spacetime, we need another coordinate system.
\layout Standard

It is a standard result that the singularity in the Schwarzschild metric\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:du dv metric}

\end_inset 

) which occurs at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2M$
\end_inset 

 is merely a 
\series bold 
coordinate singularity
\series default 
 since a suitable change of coordinates yields a metric regular at the BH
 horizon.
 For instance, an observer freely falling into the black hole would see
 a normal, finitely curved space while crossing the horizon line 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2M$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore one is motivated to consider a coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{t},\bar{r}\right)$
\end_inset 

 that describes the proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{t}$
\end_inset 

 and the proper distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{r}$
\end_inset 

 measured by a freely falling observer.
 A suitable coordinate system is the 
\series bold 
Kruskal frame
\series default 
.
 We omit the construction of the Kruskal frame
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed false

\layout Standard

A detailed derivation can be found, for instance, in 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
S
\end_inset 

31 of the book 
\emph on 
Gravitation
\emph default 
 by 
\noun on 
C.W.
 Misner, K.
 Thorne,
\noun default 
 and 
\noun on 
J.
 Wheeler
\noun default 
 (W.
 H.
 Freeman, San Francisco, 1973).
\end_inset 

 and write only the final formulae.
 The Kruskal lightcone coordinates
\begin_inset Formula \[
\bar{u}\equiv\bar{t}-\bar{r},\quad\bar{v}\equiv\bar{t}+\bar{r}\]

\end_inset 

are related to the tortoise lightcone coordinates\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:u v t rstar def}

\end_inset 

) by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\bar{u}=-4M\exp\left(-\frac{u}{4M}\right),\quad\bar{v}=4M\exp\left(\frac{v}{4M}\right).\label{eq:ubar vbar def}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{v}$
\end_inset 

 vary in the intervals
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
-\infty<\bar{u}<0,\quad0<\bar{v}<+\infty.\label{eq:ubar vbar ranges}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The inverse relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right)$
\end_inset 

 and the tortoise coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,r^{*}\right)$
\end_inset 

 is then found from Eqs.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:r tortoise def 1}

\end_inset 

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ubar vbar def}

\end_inset 

):
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
t & =2M\ln\left(-\frac{\bar{v}}{\bar{u}}\right),\nonumber \\
\exp\left(-\frac{r^{*}}{2M}\right) & =-\frac{\exp\left(1-\frac{r}{2M}\right)}{1-\frac{r}{2M}}=-\frac{16M^{2}}{\bar{u}\bar{v}}.\label{eq:rstar ubar vbar}\end{align}

\end_inset 

The BH horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2M$
\end_inset 

 corresponds to the lines 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{v}=0$
\end_inset 

.
 To examine the spacetime near the horizon, we need to rewrite the metric
 in the Kruskal coordinates.
 With the substitution
\begin_inset Formula \[
u=-4M\ln\left(-\frac{\bar{u}}{4M}\right),\quad v=4M\ln\frac{\bar{v}}{4M},\]

\end_inset 

the metric\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:du dv metric}

\end_inset 

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
ds^{2}=-\frac{16M^{2}}{\bar{u}\bar{v}}\left(1-\frac{2M}{r}\right)d\bar{u}\, d\bar{v}.\]

\end_inset 

 Using Eqs.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:r tortoise def 1}

\end_inset 

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:rstar ubar vbar}

\end_inset 

), after some algebra we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ds^{2}=\frac{2M}{r}\exp\left(1-\frac{r}{2M}\right)d\bar{u}\, d\bar{v},\label{eq:dubar dvbar metric}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where it is implied that the Schwarzschild coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 is expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{v}$
\end_inset 

 using the relation (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:rstar ubar vbar}

\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

It follows from Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dubar dvbar metric}

\end_inset 

) that at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2M$
\end_inset 

 the metric is 
\begin_inset Formula $ds^{2}=d\bar{u}\, d\bar{v}$
\end_inset 

, the same as in the Minkowski spacetime.
 Although the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u},\bar{v}$
\end_inset 

 were originally defined in the ranges\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ubar vbar ranges}

\end_inset 

), there is no singularity at 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}=0$
\end_inset 

 or at 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{v}=0$
\end_inset 

, and therefore the coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bar{u},\bar{v})$
\end_inset 

 may be extended to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}>0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{v}<0$
\end_inset 

.
 Thus the Kruskal coordinates cover a larger patch of the spacetime than
 the tortoise coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,r^{*})$
\end_inset 

.
 For instance, Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:rstar ubar vbar}

\end_inset 

) relates 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u},\bar{v}$
\end_inset 

 also for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<r<2M$
\end_inset 

, even though 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}$
\end_inset 

 is undefined for these 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, the Kruskal frame covers also the interior of the black hole.
\layout Standard

Since the metric\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dubar dvbar metric}

\end_inset 

) is conformally flat, the action and the classical field equations for
 a conformally coupled field in the Kruskal frame have the same form as
 in the tortoise coordinates.
 For instance, the general solution for the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset 

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right)=A\left(\bar{u}\right)+B\left(\bar{v}\right)$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

We note that Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ubar vbar def}

\end_inset 

) is similar to the definition\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:ubar vbar u v}

\end_inset 

) of the proper frame for a uniformly accelerated observer.
 The formal analogy is exact if we set 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv(4M)^{-1}$
\end_inset 

.
 Note that a freely falling observer (with the worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{r}=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset 

) has zero proper acceleration.
 On the other hand, a spaceship remaining at a fixed position relative to
 the BH must keep its engine running at a constant thrust and thus has constant
 proper acceleration.
 To make the analogy with the Unruh effect more apparent, we chose the notation
 in which the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right)$
\end_inset 

 always refer to freely falling observers while the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)$
\end_inset 

 describe accelerated frames.
\layout Subsection

Field quantization
\layout Standard

In the previous section we introduced two coordinate systems corresponding
 to a locally inertial observer (the Kruskal frame) and a locally accelerated
 observer (the tortoise frame).
 Now we quantize the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset 

 in these two frames and compare the respective vacuum states.
 The considerations are formally quite similar to those in Chapter\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cha:08The-Unruh-effect}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

To quantize the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset 

, it is convenient to employ the lightcone mode expansions (defined in Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Lightcone-mode-expansions}

\end_inset 

) in the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right)$
\end_inset 

.
 Because of the intentionally chosen notation, the relations\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi lc exp lab}

\end_inset 

) and (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:phi lc exp Ri}

\end_inset 

) can be directly used to describe the quantized field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 in the BH spacetime.
 
\layout Standard

The lightcone mode expansion in the tortoise coordinates is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\phi}(u,v)=\int_{0}^{+\infty}\!\frac{d\Omega}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\Omega}}\left[e^{-i\Omega u}\hat{b}_{\Omega}^{-}+H.c.+e^{-i\Omega v}\hat{b}_{-\Omega}^{-}+H.c.\right],\]

\end_inset 

where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $H.c.$
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 denotes the Hermitian conjugate terms.
 The operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\pm\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 correspond to particles detected by a stationary observer at a constant
 distance from the BH.
 The role of this observer is completely analogous to that of the uniformly
 accelerated observer considered in Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Kinematics-of-accelerated}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The lightcone mode expansion in the Kruskal coordinates is
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\phi}\left(\bar{u},\bar{v}\right)=\int_{0}^{+\infty}\!\frac{d\omega}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\omega}}\left[e^{-i\omega\bar{u}}\hat{a}_{\omega}^{-}+H.c.+e^{-i\omega\bar{v}}\hat{a}_{-\omega}^{-}+H.c.\right].\]

\end_inset 

 The operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\pm\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

 are related to particles registered by an observer freely falling into
 the black hole.
\layout Standard

It is clear that the two sets of creation and annihilation operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{\pm\omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{\pm\Omega}^{\pm}$
\end_inset 

