\layout Subsection

Choice of vacuum
\layout Standard

To find the expected number of particles measured by observers far outside
 of the black hole, we first need to make the correct choice of the quantum
 state of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

.
 In the present case, there are two candidate vacua, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{K}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{T}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 We shall draw on the analogy with Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Quantization-Rindler}

\end_inset 

 to justify the choice of the Kruskal vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{K}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, which is the lowest-energy state for freely falling observers, as the
 quantum state of the field.
\layout Standard

When considering a uniformly accelerated observer in the Minkowski spacetime,
 the correct choice of the vacuum state is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, which is the lowest-energy state as measured by inertial observers.
 An accelerated observer registers this state as thermally excited.
 The other vacuum state, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, can be physically realized by an accelerated vacuum preparation device
 occupying a very large volume of space.
 Consequently, the energy needed to prepare the field in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 in the whole space is infinitely large.
 If one computes the mean energy density of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, one finds (after subtracting the zero-point energy) that in the Minkowski
 frame the energy density diverges at the horizon.
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed false

\layout Standard

This result can be qualitatively understood if we recall that the Rindler
 coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\xi}$
\end_inset 

 covers an infinite range when approaching the horizon (
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\xi}\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset 

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\rightarrow-a^{-1}$
\end_inset 

).
 The zero-point energy density in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{R}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is constant in the Rindler frame and thus appears as an infinite concentration
 of energy density near the horizon in the Minkowski frame; a subtraction
 of the zero-point energy does not cure this problem.
 We omit the detailed calculation, which requires a renormalization of the
 energy-momentum tensor of the quantum field.
\end_inset 

 On the other hand, the Minkowski vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 has zero energy density everywhere.
\layout Standard

It turns out that a similar situation occurs in the BH spacetime.
 At first it may appear that the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 should be in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{T}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 which is the vacuum state selected by observers remaining at a constant
 distance from the black hole.
 However, the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{T}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 has an infinite energy density (after subtracting the zero-point energy)
 near the BH horizon.
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed false

\layout Standard

This is analogous to the divergent energy density near the horizon in the
 Rindler vacuum state.
 We again omit the required calculations.
\end_inset 

 Any energy density influences the metric via the Einstein equation.
 A divergent energy density indicates that the backreaction of the quantum
 fluctuations in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{T}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is so large near the BH horizon that the Schwarzschild metric is not a
 good approximation for the resulting spacetime.
 Thus the picture of a quantum field in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{T}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 near an almost unperturbed black hole is inconsistent.
 On the other hand, the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 in the Kruskal state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{K}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 has an everywhere finite and small energy density (when computed in the
 Schwarzschild frame after a subtraction of the zero-point energy).
 In this case, the backreaction of the quantum fluctuations on the metric
 is negligible.
 Therefore one has to employ the vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{K}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 rather than the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{T}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 to describe quantum fields in the presence of a classical black hole.
 
\layout Standard

Another argument for selecting the Kruskal vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{K}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is the consideration of a star that turns into a black hole through the
 gravitational collapse.
 Before the collapse, the spacetime is almost flat and the initial state
 of quantum fields is the naturally defined Minkowski vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{M}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 It can be shown that the final quantum state of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 after the collapse is the Kruskal vacuum.
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed true

\layout Standard

This was the pioneering calculation performed by S.
 W.
 Hawking.
\end_inset 


\layout Subsection

Hawking temperature
\layout Standard

Observers remaining at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\textrm{const}$
\end_inset 

 far away from the black hole (
\begin_inset Formula $r\gg2M$
\end_inset 

) are in an almost flat space where the natural vacuum state is the Minkowski
 one.
 The Minkowski vacuum at 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gg2M$
\end_inset 

 is approximately the same as the vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{T}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 Since the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 is in the Kruskal vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0_{K}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, these observers would register the presence of particles.
 
\layout Standard

The calculations of Sec.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:The-Unruh-temperature}

\end_inset 

 show that the temperature measured by an accelerated observer is 
\begin_inset Formula $T=a/(2\pi)$
\end_inset 

, and we have seen that the correspondence between the Rindler and the Schwarzsc
hild cases requires to set 
\begin_inset Formula $a=(4M)^{-1}$
\end_inset 

.
 It follows that observers at a fixed distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gg2M$
\end_inset 

 from the black hole detect a thermal spectrum of particles with the temperature
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
T_{H}=\frac{1}{8\pi M}.\label{eq:Hawking T}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

This temperature is known as the 
\series bold 
Hawking temperature
\series default 
.
 (Observers staying closer to the BH will see a higher temperature due to
 the inverse gravitational redshift.) 
\layout Standard

Similarly, we find that the density of observed particles with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E=k$
\end_inset 

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
n_{E}=\left[\exp\left(\frac{E}{T_{H}}\right)-1\right]^{-1}.\]

\end_inset 

This formula remains valid for massive particles with mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset 

 and momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

, after the natural replacement 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\sqrt{m^{2}+k^{2}}$
\end_inset 

.
 One can see that the particle production is significant only for particles
 with very small masses 
\begin_inset Formula $m\lesssim T_{H}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The Hawking effect is in principle measurable, although the Hawking temperature
 for plausible astrophysical black holes is extremely small.
 For instance, a black hole of one solar mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M=M_{\odot}=2\cdot10^{30}$
\end_inset 

kg has the size of order 1km and the Hawking temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{H}\approx6\cdot10^{-8}$
\end_inset 

K.
\layout Subsection

Black hole thermodynamics 
\layout Standard

In many situations, a static black hole of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset 

 behaves as a spherical body with radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2M$
\end_inset 

 and surface temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{H}$
\end_inset 

.
 According to the Stefan-Boltzmann law, a black body radiates the flux of
 energy
\begin_inset Formula \[
L=\gamma\sigma T_{H}^{4}A,\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 parametrizes the number of degrees of freedom available to the radiation,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\pi^{2}/60$
\end_inset 

 is the Stefan-Boltzmann constant in Planck units, and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
A=4\pi R^{2}=16\pi M^{2}\]

\end_inset 

is the surface area of the BH.
 The emitted flux determines the loss of energy due to radiation.
 The mass of the black hole decreases with time according to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{dM}{dt}=-L=-\frac{\gamma}{15360\pi M^{2}}.\label{eq:dMdt BH}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

The solution with the initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.M\right|_{t=0}=M_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
M(t)=M_{0}\left(1-\frac{t}{t_{L}}\right)^{1/3},\quad t_{L}\equiv5120\pi\frac{M_{0}^{3}}{\gamma}.\]

\end_inset 

This calculation suggests that black holes are fundamentally unstable objects
 with the lifetime 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{L}$
\end_inset 

 during which the BH completely evaporates.
 A calculation shows that a black hole with a Solar mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M=M_{\odot}=2\cdot10^{30}$
\end_inset 

kg has a lifetime 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{L}\sim10^{74}$
\end_inset 

s, which is far greater than the age of the universe.
\layout Subsubsection*

Laws of BH thermodynamics
\layout Standard

Prior to the discovery of the BH radiation it was already known that black
 holes require a thermodynamical description involving a nonzero intrinsic
 entropy.
 
\layout Standard

The entropy of a system is defined as the logarithm of the number of internal
 microstates of the system that are indistinguishable on the basis of macroscopi
cally available information.
 Since the gravitational field of a static black hole is completely determined
 (both inside and outside of the horizon) by the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset 

 of the BH, one might expect that a black hole has only one microstate and
 therefore its entropy is zero.
 However, this conclusion is inconsistent with the second law of thermodynamics.
 A black hole absorbs all energy that falls onto it.
 If the black hole always had zero entropy, it could absorb some thermal
 energy and decrease the entropy of the world.
 This would violate the second law unless one assumes that the black hole
 has an intrinsic entropy that grows in the process of absorption.
\layout Standard

Similar 
\emph on 
gedanken
\emph default 
 experiments involving classical general relativity and thermodynamics lead
 J.
 Bekenstein to conjecture in 1971 that a static black hole must have an
 intrinsic entropy 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{BH}$
\end_inset 

 proportional to the surface area 
\begin_inset Formula $A=16\pi M^{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 However, the coefficient of proportionality between 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{BH}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset 

 could not be computed until the discovery of the Hawking radiation.
 The precise relation between the BH entropy and the horizon area follows
 from the first law of thermodynamics,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
dE\equiv dM=T_{H}dS_{BH},\label{eq:BH 1st law}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{H}$
\end_inset 

 is the Hawking temperature for a black hole of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset 

.
 A simple calculation using Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Hawking T}

\end_inset 

) shows that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S_{BH}=4\pi M^{2}=\frac{1}{4}A.\label{eq:BH entropy}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 A black hole of one solar mass has the entropy 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\odot}\sim10^{76}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The thermodynamical law (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:BH 1st law}

\end_inset 

) suggests that in certain circumstances black holes behave as objects in
 thermal contact with their environment.
 This description applies to black holes surrounded by thermal radiation
 and to adiabatic processes of emission and absorption of heat.
 
\layout Standard

For a complete thermodynamical description of black holes, one needs an
 equation of state.
 This is provided by the relation
\begin_inset Formula \[
E(T)=M=\frac{1}{8\pi T}.\]

\end_inset 

It follows that the heat capacity of the BH is negative,
\begin_inset Formula \[
C_{BH}=\frac{\partial E}{\partial T}=-\frac{1}{8\pi T^{2}}<0.\]

\end_inset 

In other words, black holes become 
\emph on 
colder
\emph default 
 when they absorb heat.
 This unusual behavior leads to an instability of a BH surrounded by an
 
\emph on 
infinite
\emph default 
 heat reservoir (i.e.\SpecialChar ~
a heat bath with a constant temperature).
 If the heat reservoir has a lower temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T<T_{BH}$
\end_inset 

, the BH would give heat to the reservoir and become even hotter.
 The process of evaporation will not be halted by the reservoir since its
 low temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset 

 remains constant.
 On the other hand, a black hole placed inside a reservoir with a higher
 temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T>T_{BH}$
\end_inset 

 will tend to absorb radiation from the reservoir and become colder.
 The process of absorption will continue indefinitely.
 In either case, no stable equilibrium is possible.
 A black hole can be stabilized with respect to absorption or emission of
 radiation only by a reservoir with a 
\emph on 
finite
\emph default 
 heat capacity.
\layout Standard

The second law of thermodynamics now states that the combined entropy of
 all existing black holes and of all ordinary thermal matter never decreases,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\delta S_{total}=\delta S_{matter}+\sum_{k}\delta S_{BH}^{(k)}\geq0.\]

\end_inset 

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{BH}^{(k)}$
\end_inset 

 is the entropy\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:BH entropy}

\end_inset 

) of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

-th black hole.
\layout Standard

In classical general relativity it has been established that the combined
 area of all BH horizons cannot decrease in any interaction with classical
 matter (this is Hawking's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

area theorem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

).
 This statement applies not only to adiabatic processes but also to strongly
 out-of-equilibrium situations, such as a collision of black holes with
 the resulting merger.
 It is remarkable that this theorem, derived from a purely classical theory,
 assumes the form of the second law of thermodynamics when one considers
 quantum thermal effects of black holes.
 (The process of BH evaporation is not covered by the area theorem because
 it significantly involves quantum interactions.)
\layout Standard

Moreover, there is a general connection between horizons and thermodynamics
 which has not yet been completely elucidated.
 The presence of a horizon in a spacetime means that a loss of information
 occurs, since one cannot observe events beyond the horizon.
 Intuitively, a loss of information entails a growth of entropy.
 It seems to be generally true in the theory of relativity that any event
 horizon behaves as a surface with a certain entropy and emits radiation
 with a certain temperature.
 For instance, the Unruh effect considered in Chapter\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cha:08The-Unruh-effect}

\end_inset 

 can be interpreted as a thermodynamical consequence of the presence of
 a horizon in the Rindler spacetime.
 A similar thermal effect (detection of particles in the Bunch-Davies vacuum
 state) is also present in de Sitter spacetime which also has a horizon.
\layout Standard

These qualitative considerations conclude the present introductory course
 of quantum field theory in curved spacetime.
