Hilbert spaces and Dirac notation
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Hilbert-spaces-and}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Quantum operators such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}(t),\hat{q}(t)$
\end_inset 

 can be represented by linear transformations in suitable infinite-dimensional
 Hilbert spaces.
 In this section we summarize the properties of Hilbert spaces and also
 introduce the Dirac notation.
 We shall always consider complex vector spaces.
\layout Subsection

Infinite-dimensional vector spaces
\layout Standard

A vector in a 
\emph on 
finite
\emph default 
-dimensional space can be visualized as a collection of components, e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}\equiv\left(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3},a_{4}\right)$
\end_inset 

, where each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset 

 is a (complex) number.
 To describe vectors in 
\emph on 
infinite
\emph default 
-dimensional spaces, one must use infinitely many components.
 An important example of an infinite-dimensional complex vector space is
 the space 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset 

 of square-integrable functions, i.e.\SpecialChar ~
the set of all complex-valued functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(q)$
\end_inset 

 such that the integral
\begin_inset Formula \[
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\left|\psi(q)\right|^{2}dq\]

\end_inset 

converges.
 One can check that a linear combination of two such functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}\psi_{1}(q)+\lambda_{2}\psi_{2}(q)$
\end_inset 

, with constant coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1,2}$
\end_inset 

, is again an element of the same vector space.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\in L^{2}$
\end_inset 

 can be thought of as a set of infinitely many 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

components
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{q}\equiv\psi(q)$
\end_inset 

 with a continuous 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

index
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

It turns out that the space of quantum states of a point mass in quantum
 mechanics is exactly the space 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset 

 of square-integrable functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(q)$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

 is the spatial coordinate of the particle.
 In that case the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(q)$
\end_inset 

 is called the 
\series bold 
wavefunction
\series default 
.
 Quantum states of a two-particle system belong to the space of functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(q_{1},q_{2})$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1,2}$
\end_inset 

 are the coordinates of each particle.
 In quantum field theory, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

coordinates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 are field configurations 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset 

 and the wavefunction is a functional, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left[\phi(x)\right]$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Subsection

Dirac notation
\layout Standard

Linear algebra is used in many areas of physics, and the Dirac notation
 is a convenient shorthand for calculations with vectors and linear operators.
 This notation is used for both finite- and infinite-dimensional vector
 spaces.
 
\layout Standard

To denote a vector, Dirac proposed to write a symbol such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, that is, a label inside the special brackets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 Linear combinations of vectors are written as 
\begin_inset Formula $2\left|v\right\rangle -3i\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

A linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}:V\rightarrow V$
\end_inset 

 acting in the space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset 

 transforms a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 into the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 (An operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

 is 
\series bold 
linear
\series default 
 if 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{A}\left(\left|v\right\rangle +\lambda\left|w\right\rangle \right)=\hat{A}\left|v\right\rangle +\lambda\hat{A}\left|w\right\rangle \]

\end_inset 

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle ,\left|w\right\rangle \in V$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset 

.) For example, the identity operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{1}$
\end_inset 

 that does not change any vectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{1}\left|v\right\rangle =\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, is obviously a linear operator.
\layout Standard

Linear forms acting on vectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $f:V\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset 

, are 
\series bold 
covectors
\series default 
 (vectors from the dual space) and are denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle f\right|$
\end_inset 

.
 A linear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle f\right|$
\end_inset 

 acts on a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and yields the number written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f|v\rangle$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Usually a scalar product is defined in the space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset 

.
 The scalar product of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left|v\right\rangle ,\left|w\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset 

 and is a complex number.
 The scalar product establishes a correspondence between vectors and covectors:
 each vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 defines a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle v\right|$
\end_inset 

 which is the linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|w\right\rangle \rightarrow\left(\left|v\right\rangle ,\left|w\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset 

.
 So the Dirac notation allows us to write scalar products somewhat more
 concisely as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left|v\right\rangle ,\left|w\right\rangle \right)=\left\langle v|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

 is a linear operator, the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle v\right|\hat{A}\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 means the scalar product of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle v\right|\hat{A}\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is also called the 
\series bold 
matrix element
\series default 
 of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

 with respect to the states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The Dirac notation is convenient because the labels inside the brackets
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|...\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 are typographically separated from other symbols in a formula.
 So for instance one might denote specific vectors by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 (eigenvectors with integer eigenvalues), or by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a_{i}b_{j}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, or even by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|_{(\textrm{out})}n_{1},n_{2},...\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, without risk of confusion.
 Note that the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is the commonly used designation for the vacuum state, rather than the
 zero vector; the latter is denoted simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is an eigenvector of an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset 

, one writes
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{A}\left|v\right\rangle =v\left|v\right\rangle .\]

\end_inset 

There is no confusion between the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset 

 (which is a number) and the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 labeled by its eigenvalue.
 
\layout Subsection

Hermiticity 
\layout Standard

The scalar product in a complex vector space is 
\series bold 
Hermitian
\series default 
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\langle v|w\right\rangle \right)^{*}=\left\langle w|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 for all vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 (the asterisk 
\begin_inset Formula $^{*}$
\end_inset 

 denotes the complex conjugation).
 In that case the 
\series bold 
norm
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle v|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is a real number.
\layout Standard

A Hermitian scalar product allows one to define the 
\series bold 
Hermitian conjugate
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset 

 of an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

 via the identity
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\langle v\right|\hat{A}^{\dagger}\left|w\right\rangle =\left(\left\langle w\right|\hat{A}\left|v\right\rangle \right)^{*},\]

\end_inset 

 which should hold for all vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 Note that an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset 

 is uniquely specified if its matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle v\right|\hat{A}^{\dagger}\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 with respect to all vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 are known.
 For example, it is easy to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{1}^{\dagger}=\hat{1}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The operation of Hermitian conjugation has the properties 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\hat{A}+\hat{B})^{\dagger}=\hat{A}^{\dagger}+\hat{B}^{\dagger};\quad(\lambda\hat{A})^{\dagger}=\lambda^{*}\hat{A}^{\dagger};\quad(\hat{A}\hat{B})^{\dagger}=\hat{B}^{\dagger}\hat{A}^{\dagger}.\]

\end_inset 

 An operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

 is called 
\series bold 
Hermitian
\series default 
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{\dagger}=\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

, 
\series bold 
anti-Hermitian
\series default 
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{\dagger}=-\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\series bold 
unitary
\series default 
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{\dagger}\hat{A}=\hat{A}\hat{A}^{\dagger}=\hat{1}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

According to a postulate of quantum mechanics, the result of a measurement
 of some quantity is always an eigenvalue of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

 corresponding to that quantity.
 Eigenvalues of a Hermitian operator are always real.
 This motivates an important assumption made in quantum mechanics: the operators
 corresponding to all observables are Hermitian.
 
\layout Standard
