Eigenvectors of a Hermitian operator corresponding to different eigenvalues
 are always orthogonal.
 This is easy to prove: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 are eigenvectors of a Hermitian operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset 

 with eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset 

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1,2}$
\end_inset 

 are real, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle v_{1}\right|\hat{A}=v_{1}\left\langle v_{1}\right|$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle v_{1}\right|\hat{A}\left|v_{2}\right\rangle =v_{2}\left\langle v_{1}|v_{2}\right\rangle =v_{1}\left\langle v_{1}|v_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle v_{1}|v_{2}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset 

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}\neq v_{2}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Subsection

Hilbert spaces
\layout Standard

In an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset 

-dimensional vector space one can find a finite set of basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e_{N}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 such that any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is uniquely expressed as a linear combination 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|v\right\rangle =\sum_{n=1}^{N}v_{n}\left|e_{n}\right\rangle .\]

\end_inset 

The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are called 
\series bold 
components
\series default 
 of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 in the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left|e_{n}\right\rangle \right\} $
\end_inset 

.
 In an orthonormal basis satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle e_{m}|e_{n}\right\rangle =\delta_{mn}$
\end_inset 

, the scalar product of two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|w\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is expressed through their components 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{n}$
\end_inset 

 as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\langle v|w\right\rangle =\sum_{n=1}^{N}v_{n}^{*}w_{n}.\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

By definition, a vector space is infinite-dimensional if no finite set of
 vectors can serve as a basis.
 In that case, one might expect to have an infinite basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

, ..., such that any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is uniquely expressible as an infinite linear combination
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|v\right\rangle =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}v_{n}\left|e_{n}\right\rangle .\label{eq:vector v series}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

However, the convergence of this infinite series is a nontrivial issue.
 For instance, if the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|e_{n}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 are orthonormal, then the norm of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\langle v|v\right\rangle =\left(\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}v_{m}^{*}\left\langle e_{n}\right|\right)\left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}v_{n}\left|e_{n}\right\rangle \right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\left|v_{n}\right|^{2}.\label{eq:norm series}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

This series must converge if the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 has a finite norm, so the numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n}$
\end_inset 

 cannot be arbitrary.
 We cannot expect that e.g.\SpecialChar ~
the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}n^{2}\left|e_{n}\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 represents a well-defined vector.
 Now, if the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n}$
\end_inset 

 do fall off sufficiently rapidly so that the series\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:norm series}

\end_inset 

) is finite, it may seem plausible that the infinite linear combination\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:vector v series}

\end_inset 

) converges and uniquely specifies the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

.
 However, this statement does not hold in all infinite-dimensional spaces.
 The required properties of the vector space are known in functional analysis
 as completeness and separability.
