\layout Standard

A normed vector space is 
\series bold 
complete
\series default 
 if all norm-convergent (Cauchy) sequences in it converge to a limit; then
 all norm-convergent infinite sums always have an unique vector as their
 limit.
 The space is 
\series bold 
separable
\series default 
 if there exists a countable set of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left|e_{n}\right\rangle \right\} $
\end_inset 

 which is everywhere dense in the space.
 Separability ensures that that all vectors can be approximated arbitrarily
 well by 
\emph on 
finite
\emph default 
 combinations of the basis vectors.
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

A 
\series bold 
Hilbert space
\series default 
 is a complete vector space with a Hermitian scalar product.
 When defining a quantum theory, one always chooses a separable Hilbert
 space as the space of quantum states.
 In that case, there exists a countable basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left|e_{n}\right\rangle \right\} $
\end_inset 

 and all vectors can be expanded as in Eq.\SpecialChar ~
(
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:vector v series}

\end_inset 

).
 Once an orthonormal basis is chosen, all vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle $
\end_inset 

 are unambiguously represented by collections 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v_{1},v_{2},...\right)$
\end_inset 

 of their components.
 Therefore a separable Hilbert space can be visualized as the space of infinite
 rows of complex numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v\right\rangle \equiv\left(v_{1},v_{2},...\right)$
\end_inset 

, such that the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\left|v_{n}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset 

 converges.
 The convergence requirement guarantees that every scalar product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle v|w\right\rangle =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}v_{n}^{*}w_{n}$
\end_inset 

 is finite.
